<Folder><name>Nature &amp; sights</name>
<Placemark><name>Jotunheimvegen (Vinstre toll road)</name><description>45 km summer-only gravel toll road from Skåbu to Bygdin, built in the 1950s to replace the milk boat that carried dairy across lakes Sandvatnet and Vinstri: the literal origin of the 'milk road' theme. Easy, well-graded gravel along the lake shores with Jotunheimen's peaks growing on the horizon; toll applies to cars (120 kr in 2024), free for cyclists, open from late June. The Roros route rides its eastern stretch along Vinstre to Bygdin. [Near: Haugseter]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.15,61.38,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Lake Vinstre and Haugseter Fjellstue</name><description>Jotunheimvegen runs along the northern shore of lake Vinstre (Vinstervatn, ~1030 m), a wide mountain lake dotted with old fishing hamlets and stølar. Haugseter Fjellstue mid-lake is the classic food-and-bed stop on this leg, 14 km before Bygdin; good swimming and trout fishing. [Near: Beitostolen]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.984,61.3424,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Bygdin quay and M/B Bitihorn</name><description>Where Jotunheimvegen meets Fv51 at the east end of lake Bygdin (1060 m), beneath Bitihorn, with the historic Bygdin Høifjellshotell on the shore. M/B Bitihorn, in service since 1912 and the highest scheduled boat service in Northern Europe, sails the 25 km lake via Torfinnsbu to Eidsbugarden deep into southern Jotunheimen; two departures daily from late June, a worthwhile rest-day cruise. [Detour: on route; optional boat cruise ~3.5 h return to Eidsbugarden (1 h 45 each way) | Near: Beitostolen]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.8011,61.3276,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Bitihorn summit hike</name><description>The 1607 m horn that dominates the Bygdin-Beitostølen skyline, with a moderately demanding walk-up (no scrambling, ~550 m gain, 4 km each way) and one of Valdres' best panoramas over lake Bygdin and the southern Jotunheimen 2000-ers. Trailhead parking is right on Fv51 about 10 km north of Beitostølen, so it slots straight into the riding day. [Detour: hike, 3-5 h return from Fv51 trailhead (on route) | Near: Beitostolen]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.799,61.301,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Synshorn Via Ferrata</name><description>Popular via ferrata climbing iron rungs up the near-vertical face of Synshorn between lakes Bygdin and Vinstre to the ~1460 m summit. Guided trips run June-September, 3-4 h with ~400 m of climbing, no prior climbing experience needed (minimum age applies); book via synshorn.no. [Detour: guided activity, 3-4 h; start near Bygdin on route | Near: Beitostolen]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.7972,61.3401,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Rjupa rest area, Valdresflye</name><description>Architect-designed rest stop (Knut Hjeltnes) on the Norwegian Scenic Route Valdresflye just above Bygdin, with a panorama over the old mountain hamlets along lake Vinstre and back across Valdres. Wheelchair accessible; also a trailhead for walks onto the plateau. [Near: Beitostolen]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.8127,61.3431,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Flye 1389 (Valdresflye high point)</name><description>The highest point of the Valdresflye scenic road at 1389 m (Norway's second-highest mountain pass), where Fv51 floats above the treeless plateau with views to Besshøe, Tjønnholstinden and Rasletinden. The modern Flye 1389 cafe at the top serves local food from Valdres and Gudbrandsdalen: a natural mid-climb reward on the ride to Gjendesheim. [Near: Gjendesheim]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.8106,61.3895,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Vargebakkane viewpoint</name><description>Pull-off on the northern slope of Valdresflye (~1100 m) as the road drops toward Gjendesheim, with a head-on view of the 2000 m peaks, Knutshøe, lake Nedre Leirungen and the Besseggen ridge. Doubles as the Knutshøe trailhead (Vargbakken parking, ~4 km south of the Gjendesheim exit). [Near: Gjendesheim]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.8055,61.4564,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Knutshøe ridge hike</name><description>The 'little sister of Besseggen': a 1517 m grassy-then-rocky ridge squeezed between lake Gjende and the Leirungen lakes, with some easy scrambling and big views over emerald Gjende. No boat or booking needed, far quieter than Besseggen; the ~13 km loop (690 m gain) starts at Vargbakken parking right on Fv51. Golden eagles nest here, so locals advise saving it for after 1 July (fine for mid-July). [Detour: hike, 4-6 h loop from Vargebakkane on Fv51 | Near: Gjendesheim]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.7549,61.48,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Gjendesheim - Jotunheimen NP eastern gateway</name><description>DNT's most visited staffed lodge north of the Alps (est. 1878, 156 beds), at ~1000 m on the east end of lake Gjende just off Fv51: the main eastern entry to Jotunheimen National Park, home to Norway's highest peaks and 60+ glaciers. Beds, hearty dinners and the Besseggen and Gjende boat trailheads make it the obvious overnight for a hiking day. [Detour: on route (end of the Fv51 Valdresflye leg) | Near: Gjendesheim]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.8126,61.4943,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Lake Gjende and the Gjende boats</name><description>An 18 km glacial lake famous for its vivid emerald-green colour from glacier-milled rock flour, often called Norway's most beautiful mountain lake. Passenger boats shuttle Gjendesheim-Memurubu-Gjendebu, with up to 7-8 departures daily to Memurubu in high season (the classic Besseggen approach); pre-book at gjende.no as July departures sell out. [Detour: on route at Gjendesheim; boat ~20-45 min each way | Near: Gjendesheim]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.756,61.4869,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Besseggen ridge</name><description>Norway's most famous day hike (up to ~60,000 walkers/year): take the morning boat to Memurubu and walk the 14 km ridge back to Gjendesheim, climbing the dramatic crest between green Gjende and blue Bessvatnet, the two lakes separated by 400 vertical metres. Immortalised by Ibsen's Peer Gynt, who rode a reindeer buck along the ridge; allow a full day and book the boat well ahead for mid-July. [Detour: hike, 6-8 h plus boat to Memurubu (book gjende.no) | Near: Gjendesheim]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.7319,61.5042,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Slettefjellet high point (1315 m)</name><description>The highest point of the whole Mjølkevegen at 1315 m, reached by a stiff climb on Slettefjellvegen between Beitostølen and Vang (one of the route's most demanding sections); picnic spot at the top with a sweeping panorama back over the Jotunheimen massif before the steep descent toward Vang and Vangsmjøse. A Mjølkevegen rest shelter sits shortly before Mugnestølen partway along. [Near: Beitostolen]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.7468,61.2156,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Høre stave church</name><description>12th-century stave church (timber dendro-dated 1179, matching a runic inscription about the Battle of Kalvskinnet) on the hillside above Ryfoss, passed on the steep descent from Slettefjell. One of Valdres' cluster of surviving stave churches, rich in medieval dragon and lion carvings; a two-minute culture stop between the day's two big climbs. [Detour: on route (just off the Slettefjell descent) | Near: Vaset]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.8049,61.1532,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Syndinstøga</name><description>Mountain lodge and cafe on the Syndin lakes in the old stølsgrend above Ryfoss, a Mjølkevegen institution that began in 1963 by serving rømmegrøt and waffles in the farmhouse living room; today it has a shop, cafe and 22 beds, with rømmegrøt with cured meat still the signature dish. Ideally placed at the top of the steep Ryfoss-Syndin climb, ~20 km before Vaset. [Detour: on route (Syndin lakes) | Near: Vaset]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.7388,61.0899,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Lisjordetstølen (open summer farm)</name><description>Working mountain dairy on Stølsvidda, the area with the most active summer farms in Northern Europe, with 25 milking cows plus calves, goats, rabbits, chickens and a llama; open daily 12:00-18:00 throughout July with coffee and stølskost (simple farm food), and evening milking to watch 18:00-19:00 on selected days (advance sign-up, fills fast). On Panoramavegen at Rensenn between Vaset and Hemsedal: peak on-theme stop for a 'milk road' trip. [Detour: +15 km return from Vaset on Panoramavegen | Near: Vaset]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.8874,60.9565,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Stubbesetstølen (open summer farm)</name><description>Old støl next to Vasetstølen on Panoramavegen at Vaset, open several days a week in summer: greet the animals and buy farm-made goat cheese, butter, lefse and cakes baked from old recipes in the farm bakery. The zero-detour option for stocking up on støl produce at the overnight stop. [Detour: on route at Vaset | Near: Vaset]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.9783,60.9888,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Langestølen Kolonial og Kafé</name><description>Summer-season farm shop and cafe on Tisleivegen by Tisleifjorden in Tisleidalen, a popular stop for Mjølkevegen cyclists serving rømmegrøt and fresh waffles the traditional way; also sells homemade kuruv (Valdres cured sausage), pultost, butter and rømme, plus fishing permits and gear. Open four months over summer (plus winter holidays and Easter). [Detour: +13 km south of Vaset, or fold into the Vaset-Gol leg (it lies on the Mjølkevegen Vaset-Golsfjellet stage) | Near: Vaset]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.9417,60.8766,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Lomen Stave Church</name><description>Stave church from c. 1192 above the Slidre valley, with three lavishly carved portals, chancel arches and column capitals; open daily in summer with guides (2025 season: mid-June to mid-August, 10:00-18:00, adults NOK 130), exterior viewable year-round. The nearer-to-route Hegge stave church sits on the road up to Beitostolen on your previous leg, so Lomen is the Valdres stave church to target from Vaset. [Detour: ~22 km each way by road from Vaset (descend to Ron on Slidrefjorden, then E16 north-west); half-day round trip, easiest folded into the Beitostolen-Vaset day | Near: Vaset]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.92395,61.13485,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Stolsvidda summer farm plateau</name><description>The Vaset-Golsfjellet stage crosses one of Norway's largest active summer-farming (stol) areas, a network of close to 200 stols with cows and sheep grazing free: summer-farm stops around Langestolen (cafe and small store), Jaslangen and Trollhovd, and long views back to Jotunheimen. This is the landscape that gives Mjolkevegen (the Milk Road) its name. [Detour: On route (the Vaset-Gol stage runs straight across it) | Near: Vaset]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.9,60.94,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Tisleifjorden</name><description>Large regulated mountain lake (13.4 km2, 821 m) between Stolsvidda and Golsfjellet, the best swim-and-picnic stop of the Vaset-Gol day. The Vasskanten service house by Oset Fjellhotell at the lake's south-east end has changing facilities, charging and snacks, with SUP, canoe and motorboat hire on the lake and a lakeside sauna at the nearby Vasskanten cafe. The wider Golsfjellet plateau holds 20+ fishable lakes and rivers (season 1 Jun-10 Sep). [Detour: On route; the Mjolkevegen meets the lake at the Oset/Vasskanten end | Near: Gol]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.993,60.8355,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Gol Stave Church replica (Storoyne)</name><description>Faithful 1994 copy of Gol's medieval stave church (the original, dated c. 1157-1216, was rescued in the 1880s and now stands at the Norwegian Folk Museum in Oslo), built by local craftsmen over roughly ten years of work. It stands at Storoyne riverside park in Gol centre with a stave-church architecture exhibition added in 2023; open daily 12:00-18:00 from 20 June to 20 August, grounds accessible anytime, free parking at Hallingparken. [Detour: On route, in Gol centre | Near: Gol]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.94772,60.69793,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Torpo Stave Church</name><description>Built c. 1192, the oldest building in Hallingdal and the valley's only surviving original stave church, famous for its painted 13th-century ceiling canopy depicting the legend of St Margaret. The nave was saved by the Society for the Preservation of Norwegian Ancient Monuments (Fortidsminneforeningen) when the chancel was demolished in 1880; open daily 10:00-18:00 from 1 June to 31 August 2026, guided tours bookable through Fortidsminneforeningen. [Detour: On route: Torpo village sits on the Gol-Al valley road ~15 km west of Gol, church 200 m off the road | Near: Gol]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.70838,60.66405,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Al Bygdamuseum (Leksvol)</name><description>Open-air museum of 30 historic buildings around the c. 1600 Leksvol farmhouse just above Al centre, covering Hallingdal farm life from valley farmhouse to mountain stol and cotter's plot. Open 1 July to 15 August 2026 (guided openings Mon/Tue/Thu 11:00-16:00 in peak weeks), so it falls inside your trip window. [Detour: ~1 km gentle climb west of Al centre, midway on the Gol-Geilo valley ride | Near: Gol]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.54632,60.62987,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Strandafjorden bathing place</name><description>The Hallingdal valley ride's best swimming stop: sandy shore, diving board and grassy picnic areas on Strandafjorden, 2 km west of Al beside Hallingdal Feriepark (Topcamp), signposted from Rv7 at Vangebrua. Note the lake is fed by the hydropower-regulated Hallingdalselva, so water levels can rise without warning. [Detour: On route, 2 km west of Al, a few hundred metres off Rv7 | Near: Geilo]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.53336,60.62036,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Hol Old Church</name><description>Hol's oldest church, 13th-century in origin: the apse survives from the original stave church, with Renaissance pulpit and font (1697) and a 1703 altarpiece; the parish church until the new Hol church at Hagafoss took over in 1924, still used for summer services. A quiet, genuinely old counterpoint to the busier stave churches. [Detour: ~3.5 km each way off Rv7 at Hagafoss on the Al-Geilo leg (about 7 km round trip) | Near: Geilo]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.30019,60.61507,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Hallingskarvet National Park</name><description>450 km2 national park (established 2006) around the 35 km Hallingskarvet massif, topped by Folarskardnuten at 1,933 m, the highest point in Buskerud. The wall of the Skarvet dominates the skyline for your whole Geilo-Haugastol ride; main summer entry is via Prestholtseter, with other access from Haugastol (Rv7) and Storestolen (road 50). [Detour: Visible from the route throughout; nearest entry point Prestholtseter, ~25 min from Geilo by summer toll road | Near: Geilo]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.87,60.6,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Prestholtskardet sherpa steps hike (from Prestholtseter)</name><description>Signature Hallingskarvet hike: about 2,000 stone steps laid by sherpas in 2013 climb 3 km from Prestholtseter (1,242 m) to the Prestholtskardet gap at ~1,600 m, with views over Hallingdal and Hardangervidda (the Hardangerjokulen glacier on clear days); a loop variant (Prestholtrunden) returns behind the skard. Prestholtseter itself is a 1904 summer-farm cafe serving traditional food and home baking, open daily roughly early July to mid-August (then autumn weekends); the toll road normally opens around 1 July, so it should be open for a mid-July visit. [Detour: ~12 km / 20-25 min from Geilo up a summer-only toll road, cash or Vipps (a stiff but ridable gravel climb); hike 2-3 h, allow a half day | Near: Geilo]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.06494,60.54925,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Ustedalsfjorden Rundt with Fekjo cultural heritage park</name><description>Easy 10 km loop around Geilo's lake, about 1 hour by bike or 2-3 on foot, with picnic spots and swimming along the way. On the south shore at Fekjo the trail passes a cluster of roughly 20 Viking-age burial mounds (excavated finds dated to the 900s, most of them women's graves) plus traces of iron-working and charcoal pits. [Detour: Starts and ends in Geilo centre; ideal rest-day or evening loop | Near: Geilo]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.157,60.526,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Geilojordet historic farmstead</name><description>Free open-air farmstead in central Geilo with nine buildings from the 1700s-1900s gathered from farms in Hol and Al, plus a playground, farm animals and free storytelling theatre in summer. Summer cafe with traditional food (sour-cream porridge, pancakes) runs June to August, 11:00-16:00. [Detour: None; in Geilo centre by the church (Skurdalsvegen 2) | Near: Geilo]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.212,60.535,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Kikut - Hakkesetstolen and Bjodnahovda viewpoint</name><description>From the Kikut cabin area south-east of Geilo, an easy family walk (partly wood-chipped and stroller-friendly) leads to Hakkesetstolen fjellstugu (summer food service) and on to the Bjodnahovda viewpoint, with views over Geilo, Ustedalsfjorden and across to Hallingskarvet. A low-effort way to get above the treeline if you skip the bigger Prestholt hike; also reachable from the Vestlia chairlift. [Detour: ~6 km by road from Geilo centre to the Kikut trailhead (Skurdalsvegen toward road 40), then a 2-3 km walk | Near: Geilo]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.21649,60.5019,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Haugastol - Rallarvegen kilometre zero</name><description>Official start of the 80 km Rallarvegen at ~990 m: the navvies' construction road built for the Bergen Railway around the turn of the century (the road reached Haugastol by 1902), opened as a cycle route in 1974 and now Norway's most popular bike ride. Haugastol Turistsenter at the trailhead handles bike hire, service and luggage logistics before the high-mountain leg to Finse. [Detour: On route; this is where your middle section hands over to the Rallarvegen | Near: Haugastol]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.86314,60.51202,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Hardangervidda National Park (northern edge)</name><description>Mainland Norway's largest national park (3,422 sq km) on northern Europe's biggest mountain plateau, home to Europe's largest wild reindeer herd. The Rallarvegen between Haugastol and Finse runs along the plateau's northern rim (the formal park boundary lies a few km south of the trail): treeless tundra, lakes, and snow patches even in July. No fences or gates, the landscape IS the attraction. Watch for reindeer south of the trail around the Krækkja hut area. [Detour: 0 km, the Haugastol-Finse stage rides the plateau's northern rim just outside the park boundary | Near: Haugastol]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.72,60.5,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Finse and Finse 1222 (Star Wars Hoth location)</name><description>Highest station on the Bergen Line at 1,222 m, road-free, reachable only by rail or Rallarvegen. The Hoth claim is verified: Empire Strikes Back ice-planet scenes were shot on and around Hardangerjokulen from 5 March 1979, with cast and crew based at the Finse 1222 hotel (opened 1909). Hotel serves meals and beds if weather turns; the village hosts recurring Star Wars fan gatherings (Visit Hoth, Hoth Strikes Back). [Detour: 0 km, on route; overnight or lunch stop | Near: Finse]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.5039,60.6019,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Rallarmuseet Finse (Navvy Museum)</name><description>Museum at Finse station on the navvies who built the Bergen Line 1894-1909, with an authentic forge, construction barracks, and exhibitions on the fight against the snow with historic snow-clearing machinery. Open early July to mid-September; entry around NOK 40. The right context stop before riding the road those navvies built. [Detour: 0 km, at Finse station; 30-60 min visit | Near: Finse]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.5057,60.6027,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Hardangerjokulen glacier (Blaisen/Midtdalsbreen views)</name><description>Mainland Norway's sixth-largest glacier (ice cap to 1,863 m) dominating the skyline south of Finse. Best free views are from Finsevatnet lakeshore and the Rallarvegen west of Finse. The Blaisen and Midtdalsbreen tongues are walkable to the ice edge (do not go onto the ice unguided). This is the actual Hoth filming terrain. [Detour: Visible from route; ice-edge walk ~2 hr round trip on foot from Finse | Near: Finse]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.468,60.567,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Guided glacier hike with Joklagutane</name><description>Bookable in July: Joklagutane runs guided glacier walks on Hardangerjokulen (Blaisen) daily from early July, departing Finse railway station around 11:00. 6-7 hrs, ~16 km, guide/glacier equipment/insurance included, min age 12, good fitness needed. Book ahead at joklagutane.no (+47 993 31 222). Doing this means a full extra day at Finse, plan the itinerary around it. [Detour: Full day (6-7 hrs) from Finse; requires a rest/short-ride day | Near: Finse]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.5039,60.6019,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Fagernut vokterbolig (waffle cottage)</name><description>Stone line-watchman's cottage from 1904 at 1,310 m, about 10 km west of Finse near the Rallarvegen's high point. Summer cafe serves fresh waffles and coffee plus a small exhibition on watchman family life. Verified caveat: opens daily 10:00-16:30 only from roughly mid-July depending on snow. Your ~14-15 July passage is borderline; check facebook.com/Fagernut before banking on waffles, bring cash, and carry food regardless. [Detour: 0 km, on route; 30 min stop if open | Near: Finse]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.4,60.627,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Kleivabrua stone bridge, Kleivagjelet</name><description>35 m single-span stone bridge over the Kleivagjelet ravine between Hallingskeid and Myrdal, one of the hardest engineering problems on the line and the showpiece of navvy stonework. Exposed drop beside the trail; walking the bike past the ravine is normal if you dislike heights. [Detour: 0 km, on route | Near: Finse]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.17,60.7,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Myrdalsberget 21 switchbacks (Kleva)</name><description>The famous descent: 21 tight gravel hairpins dropping from Vatnahalsen off the Myrdalsberget cliff to the valley floor at Kardal, beside river and waterfall. Surface is rough, brakes overheat, and most riders walk at least some bends, fully loaded bikepacking rigs should. Top of the switchbacks gives the classic view down Flamsdalen. Flam Zipline (1,381 m, the Nordic region's longest) runs Vatnahalsen to Kardal if one of you wants the fast way down. [Detour: 0 km, on route; allow 30-45 min for the descent | Near: Flam]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.116,60.741,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Kjosfossen waterfall</name><description>93 m main drop (225 m total) and the signature stop of the Flamsbana: trains pause 5 minutes at a platform reachable only by rail, where in summer a dancer plays the Huldra folklore spirit against the falls. From the bike route you get side views near Vatnahalsen; the full frontal view requires riding the train, an argument for taking the Flamsbana up from Flam as a day trip or for the outbound leg. [Detour: Partial view ~0 km from route; full view needs a Flamsbana ride | Near: Flam]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.131,60.742,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Flamsbana (Flam Railway), Myrdal station</name><description>20 km branch line dropping 866 m from Myrdal to the fjord, gradient 1:18, the steepest standard-gauge adhesion railway in Europe and routinely called the world's most beautiful train ride. Takes bikes when space allows. Useful three ways: bail-out if weather or mechanicals hit, the Kjosfossen view, or a luggage-free joyride from Flam after you arrive. [Detour: 0 km, Myrdal is on route; ~1 hr ride if taken | Near: Flam]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.1236,60.7342,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Flamsdalen valley descent</name><description>The ~16 km run from Kardal to the fjord: a classic U-shaped valley with the Flamselvi river (salmon-green water), waterfalls off both walls, goat farms, and the railway threading above. Gradient eases after the switchbacks, so this is fast, scenic riding. Stock up on nothing, eat in Flam. [Detour: 0 km, this is the route | Near: Flam]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.131,60.793,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Brekkefossen hike</name><description>Best effort-to-view ratio in Flam: 2 km flat along the river from the village, then 578 stone steps climbing ~200 m to the Raokjen viewpoint beside the waterfall, looking over Flam village and down the Aurlandsfjord. 1.5-2.5 hrs round trip on foot, steep and slippery when wet. Ideal recovery-day leg stretch after the ride. [Detour: 2 km from Flam centre + 1.5-2.5 hr round trip on foot | Near: Flam]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.099,60.846,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Flam Railway Museum</name><description>Free museum beside Flam station covering the 20-year construction of the Flamsbana, with an original El9 locomotive (in service 1947-1983), navvy-era photos, and an audio guide. Good 30-45 min filler while waiting for a fjord boat or train, and it closes the loop on the railway history you have been riding through since Finse. [Detour: 0 km, in Flam centre; free entry | Near: Flam]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.1136,60.8631,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Stegastein viewpoint</name><description>30 m steel-and-pine platform jutting from the mountainside 650 m above the Aurlandsfjord, the definitive aerial fjord view of the trip. By bike from Flam: ~10 km to Aurland then ~7-8 km of paved hairpins up the Aurlandsfjellet snow road, roughly 650 m of climbing, a stiff but rideable bonus climb for fit riders with unloaded bikes. Otherwise the electric shuttle/sightseeing bus from Flam runs several times daily in July (1-2 hr round trip, ~30 min at the top). [Detour: ~17 km + 650 m climb one way by bike (half day), or 1-2 hr by shuttle bus from Flam | Near: Flam]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.2114,60.9066,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Otternes farm hamlet (Otternes Bygdetun)</name><description>Clustered hamlet of 27 historic farm buildings from the 1700s, farmed in the traditional way until late in the 20th century, on a shelf above the Aurlandsfjord about 4 km from Flam on the old fjord road. In season open daily ~10:00-17:00 with guided tours four times a day and a small summer cafe, but staffing has been patchy in recent years: building interiors may be closed, and the yard and fjord view alone justify the stop. Access road is steep narrow gravel, fine by bike. [Detour: 4 km from Flam toward Aurland + short steep gravel climb; ~1 hr | Near: Flam]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.156,60.888,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Naeroyfjord UNESCO fjord cruise</name><description>The finish-line reward: 2 hr cruise from Flam harbour through the Aurlandsfjord into the Naeroyfjord, UNESCO-listed since 2005 and one of the narrowest fjords in Europe, to Gudvangen. Norway's Best sails the silent electric/hybrid sightseeing boats (Future of the Fjords, Vision of the Fjords); book ahead for July, multiple daily departures. Return to Flam by 20-min shuttle bus (~NOK 130) or boat. Cheaper alternative: Lustrabaatane runs a classic-style seasonal ferry on the same Flam-Gudvangen water. [Detour: Departs Flam harbour; half day (2 hr one way + bus or boat back) | Near: Flam]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>6.94,60.917,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Besseggen ridge hike (Gjende boat to Memurubu, hike back)</name><description>The classic loop: boat Gjendesheim-Memurubu (20 min), hike ~14 km back over the ridge, ~1,100 m ascent, 6-8 h, demanding with light scrambling between Gjende (984 m) and Bessvatnet (1,373 m). 2026 boats run 6 Jun-19 Sept (daily departures through 13 Sept), up to 8 departures/day to Memurubu; take the earliest boat. Prices: one-way NOK 260 adult, same-day Gjendesheim-Memurubu return NOK 300, luggage NOK 100/piece. Pre-booking on gjende.no is required before arrival and tickets are non-refundable; July departures sell out, so book the dated 2026 sailing (already on sale, e.g. 17 Jul 2026 listings live) as soon as the itinerary is fixed. Bring a screenshot of the ticket QR. Bikes: no official bike storage published; quay parking is free for 2 h only, long-stay parking is at Reinsvangen 1.7 km away (shuttle starts 30 min before the first boat). Practical move: ask staff at the DNT Gjendesheim lodge to stow loaded bikes (staffed lodge, lock them regardless), or send panniers across on the boat (NOK 100, ask crew where labelled bags are left at the quay). Verified: gjende.no/en/time-tables/, gjende.no/en/some-practical-information/, visitnorway.com Besseggen guide. [Detour: Gjendesheim sits ~2 km off the Mjolkevegen/Valdresflye line (Rv51), so almost no extra riding, but it costs a full day; plan an overnight at Gjendesheim DNT or Bessheim | Near: Beitostolen]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.81,61.494,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Hardangerjokulen / Blaisen guided glacier walk from Finse</name><description>Current operator is Joklagutane AS (booking site glaciertoursnorway.com). Roped glacier trek to the Blaisen arm of Hardangerjokulen: meets ~11:00 at the Finse station, back ~18:00; 6-7 h, 15-17 km round trip in unmarked high-mountain terrain. Includes guide, all glacier gear (crampons, harness, rope), insurance, small gift; min age 12; good fitness needed. Season 10 July-15 Sept, tours run essentially daily in summer, timed to Bergen Line trains. Price: web listings of NOK 650-690 trace back to 2018-era pages and are almost certainly stale; confirm current 2026 price and book at glaciertoursnorway.com (site intermittently slow/unreachable, confirmed during checking) or +47 993 31 222 / post@joklagutane.no. Timing note: season opens 10 July, riders hit Finse ~15-16 July, so it works, but book ahead. Verified: haugastol.no/en/glacier-tours (season 10 Jul-15 Sept, 11:00 meet, inclusions), geilo.com/en/activities/summer-activities/glacier-tour (15-17 km, min age 12). [Detour: Zero riding detour (Finse is on the Rallarvegen route) but it consumes a full day, 11:00-18:00; build in a second night at Finse 1222 or the DNT hut | Near: Finse]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.5041,60.6017,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Stegastein viewpoint: ride the Bjorgavegen climb or shuttle from Flam</name><description>Cantilevered platform 650 m above Aurlandsfjord; free, open 24/7, toilets on site. Ride option: from Aurlandsvangen the paved Bjorgavegen (fv243, the Aurlandsfjellet Snow Road) climbs ~9 km and ~630 m to the viewpoint (seven hairpins, busy with tourist cars); the full Aurlandsfjellet climb is 16.5 km / 1,295 m / 7.9% per climbfinder if you want the whole snow road. From Flam add ~9 km each way of flat fjord road to Aurland: budget ~38 km / 650 m+ round trip on unloaded bikes. Bus option: electric minibus tour from beside Flam railway station, 1.5 h round trip with ~25 min on the platform, from NOK 430/adult, runs year-round; book via norwaysbest.com or fjordtours.com. Verified: fjordtours.com (electric minibus, from NOK 430, 1.5 h, ~25 min at platform), climbfinder.com/en/climbs/aurlandsfjellet (16.5 km / 1,295 m / 7.9%, Stegastein at 9 km), coordinate databases (viewpoint at 60.9086, 7.2118). [Detour: Half day from Flam: ~3 h ride round trip from Flam (or 1.5 h by shuttle bus); coordinates given are the climb start in Aurlandsvangen, viewpoint itself at 60.9086, 7.2118 | Near: Flam]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.187,60.9058,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Naeroyfjord cruise Flam-Gudvangen (Norway's Best)</name><description>Premium electric sightseeing vessels (Future/Legacy of the Fjords) sail Flam-Gudvangen through Aurlandsfjord and the UNESCO-listed Naeroyfjord, ~2 h one way, multiple daily departures in July. Pricing is dynamic by date and operator: adult one-way NOK 520-595 typical (visitBergen lists NOK 550, child 4-15 NOK 275; peak-date Norway's Best fares can run higher); boat out + shuttle bus back ~NOK 760 total (bus leg ~30 min); full round trip by boat takes ~4.5-5 h and costs roughly double the single fare. Lustrabaatane also runs the leg Apr-Oct with a family ticket (~NOK 1,300 for 2+2). Book at norwaysbest.com (select date, leg, pax); July midday sailings fill, book a few days ahead. Good end-of-trip option: one-way and bus back is the time-efficient combo. Verified: flamtravelguide.com (one-way 520-595, round trip with bus 760, boat round trip 4.5-5 h), en.visitbergen.com (NOK 550 / child 275), norwaysbest.com. [Detour: Half day from Flam at trip end: ~2.5-3 h with bus return, ~4.5-5 h round trip by boat; no riding required | Near: Flam]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.1133,60.8627,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Guided sea kayak on Aurlandsfjord from Flam (Njord)</name><description>Njord Kayak Centre (seakayaknorway.com), beachside base a short walk from Flam station. Signature 3 h Fjord Paddle: NOK 1,235 adult / NOK 950 child, July departures daily 10:00, 12:00 and 15:00; shorter 2 h Family Fjord Paddle NOK 995 adult / NOK 825 child (08:30, 11:30, 17:00; runs 16 May-15 Sept, children over 5 welcome). All gear and guide included, no experience needed. Note: half-day paddles cover the Aurlandsfjord from Flam; reaching Naeroyfjord proper by kayak means a multi-day tour (e.g. Njord's 3-day Naeroyfjord kayak-camp tour, also on GetYourGuide). Book online at seakayaknorway.com or +47 913 26 628 / info@seakayaknorway.com; July slots fill, book ahead. Pairs well as a recovery-day activity after rolling into Flam. Verified: seakayaknorway.com/fjord-paddle-3-hour-guided-kayak-tour (NOK 1,235, daily 10:00/12:00/15:00 in July, family paddle NOK 995). [Detour: 3 h activity at the Flam finish line, zero riding detour; morning slot leaves the afternoon free for Stegastein or the fjord cruise | Near: Flam]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.1115,60.8632,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Prestholt sherpa steps and Skarvsenden, Hallingskarvet (Geilo half day)</name><description>Best half-day at Geilo: the Prestholt round from Prestholtseter mountain cafe (1,242 m) climbs ~2,000 stone steps built by Nepalese sherpas (2013) to the Hallingskarvet plateau rim at Skarvsenden (1,705 m); loop ~6.5 km, ~500 m ascent, 2-3.5 h, returns past an old reindeer trapping site. Trailhead is ~11 km / 25 min drive from Geilo centre: asphalt then gravel toll road (NOK 40, cash or Vipps), normally open from around 1 July, rideable on gravel bikes (~440 m climb from Geilo at ~800 m). Cafe at the trailhead serves traditional food, open daily early July to mid Aug (weekends only after that); no booking needed for the hike. Verified: geilo.com/en/hiking/national-parks/hallingskarvet-national-park, outdooractive.com Prestholtseter (coords 60.5494/8.0681, 1,242 m, cafe daily early Jul-mid Aug, road opens ~1 Jul), visitnorway.com Prestholt listings (Skarvsenden 1,705 m, toll NOK 40 cash/Vipps). [Detour: Half day from Geilo: ~22 km round-trip ride on the toll road plus 2-3.5 h hike; doable the afternoon you arrive or the morning you leave for Haugastol | Near: Geilo]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.0681,60.5494,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Gjende boat (Gjendebatane) ticket logistics, Gjendesheim quay</name><description>Standalone logistics entry for the boat that makes Besseggen work. 2026 season 6 Jun-19 Sept, daily service through 13 Sept (limited scheduled departures after, autumn extras announced later), up to 8 departures/day Gjendesheim-Memurubu (dated 2026 sailings already bookable online, e.g. mid-July listings live on gjende.no). Fares: Gjendesheim-Memurubu single NOK 260 adult / NOK 130 child, same-day return NOK 300 (child 150); Gjendesheim-Gjendebu single NOK 320, day return NOK 360; luggage NOK 100/item (buy labels on board or at the lodges); dogs free. Booking is required before arrival, tickets are non-refundable except in special circumstances, and July sailings sell out, so lock in dates early and screenshot the QR ticket. Parking: free max 2 h at the quay; long-stay at Reinsvangen 1.7 km with shuttle starting 30 min before the first boat (book shuttle online). Contact +47 61 23 92 93 / harald@gjende.no (no replies 21:30-07:00). Verified: gjende.no/en/time-tables/, gjende.no/en/some-practical-information/. [Detour: At Gjendesheim, ~2 km off the Valdresflye road; relevant only if doing Besseggen or sending luggage to Memurubu | Near: Beitostolen]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.809,61.4938,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Røros Bergstaden &amp; Røros kirke (Bergstadens Ziir)</name><description>UNESCO World Heritage mining town (listed 1980), founded on copper in 1644; the start line. The 1784 baroque church 'Bergstadens Ziir' seats about 1,600 and is one of Norway's largest churches. Entry NOK 60 (under 16 free with an adult); summer opening Tue-Sat 11:00-16:00. Organ concerts at 18:00 most evenings from 23 June (about 45 min, NOK 100 at the door, under 12 free). Entry is via the side doors 8 June-11 July due to main-door renovation, so this applies on the 9 July start day. Wandering Kjerkgata and Sleggveien's wooden houses takes 30-45 min and costs nothing. [Detour: On route, km 0 (route starts at Røros station, about 200 m away) | Near: Roros]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.3838,62.5748,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Smelthytta, Røros Museum</name><description>The rebuilt copper smelter at Malmplassen, now the main museum: working scale models of the mines, smelting process and water-powered hoists. Published schedule (2025; 2026 not yet posted): open daily 10:00-17:00 from 20 June to 15 August; adult NOK 150, under 16 free with an adult, audioguide (NO/EN/DE/FR) included. Allow about 1 hour. With the church and slag heaps this is the core of a 2-3 hour Røros morning before rolling out. [Detour: On route, km 0.1 (about 200 m off track) | Near: Roros]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.3843,62.5757,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Slegghaugan slag heaps &amp; Malmplassen</name><description>Black hills of smelting slag from 333 years of copper production (1644-1977), protected as part of the World Heritage site. Climb to the top for the best free panorama over the turf-roofed town and church; 15-20 min, always open, no ticket. [Detour: 300 m off route at km 0.1 | Near: Roros]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.3862,62.5767,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Olavsgruva mine tour (Storwartz)</name><description>Guided underground tour 50 m down and 500 m in to the Miners' Hall, through the old Nyberget mine (1650s) and the newer Olav's Mine. About 1 hour, in Norwegian and English; adult NOK 220, student/senior NOK 200 (2025 prices), under 16 free with an adult. The published 2026 schedule shows 15:00 daily for 1-19 June, with July times not yet posted at time of research, so book ahead online or on +47 72 40 61 70 (phone 10:00-15:00 daily). Mine stays cold year-round, bring a layer. Verdict: the one Røros sight that does not fit a 2-3 hour town visit; it costs a half day since it sits 13 km north-east of town, away from the route. [Detour: 13 km each way by road from Røros, opposite direction to the route; realistically a half-day add-on | Near: Roros]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.5621,62.6306,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Grådalen seter valley</name><description>The route's opening act builds in two stages: tarmac then gravel up Hådalen out of Røros, and from km 18 the track turns onto Grådalsveien, a toll gravel road (cars pay, bikes free) signed towards Grådalen and Grådalssetra. From the south end of Rambergsjøen it crosses open bare-mountain seter country, a local gravel classic, before dropping into Tufsingdalen around km 40. Active grazing, big skies, no services; the farms here do not run regular cafes, so this is a ride-through landscape rather than a stop. Verified on track roughly km 18-40, topping out around 740-790 m. [Detour: On route, km 18-40 | Near: Roros]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.696,62.387,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Tufsingdalen &amp; Mauritz Landhandel</name><description>Quiet farming valley in Os municipality west of Lake Femund; the route drops into it off Grådalen and turns west at about km 40. Mauritz Landhandel (Kopparleden 6075, on the old copper-road route 26) is the valley's country store and the practical reason to swing by: staffed daytime, self-service access around the clock outside staffed hours, useful if you pass outside shop hours. Resupply context: after this the on-route options before Alvdal (km 163) are thin; DNT's self-service Ellefsplass cabin at km 75 stocks provisions for members, and the Bergset shops in Rendalen (Joker and Coop Marked) are a ~3 km detour off the track near km 125. [Detour: About 2 km south of the route's westward turn at km 40 | Near: Tufsingdalen]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.73532,62.28634,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Femundsmarka National Park (across Lake Femund)</name><description>Famous wilderness of glacier-scoured pine forest and lakes on the EAST side of Femunden, Norway's third-largest lake and largest natural one (203 km2, about 60 km long); park established 1971. Geometry check: the route never touches it. Closest practical access is Synnervika quay at the lake's north end (coordinates given), about 10 km east of the track near km 30, where the heritage boat M/S Fæmund II (on the lake since 1905, bikes allowed) starts its daily round trip at 09:00 in season, calling at Elgå on the park side. Verdict: worth knowing it is there, but it only makes sense with a full extra day; on this itinerary, admire Femund's hills from the Grådalen-Tufsingdalen descent and keep rolling. [Detour: 10-12 km each way to Synnervika quay from track km ~30, plus boat crossing; not practical without adding a day | Near: Tufsingdalen]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.8815,62.4161,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Storlegda &amp; Sølendalen high country (Rendalen)</name><description>The wilderness heart of the leg. From Øversjødalen (km ~74, where DNT's self-service Ellefsplass cabin sits 150 m off track at km 75; 12 beds, provisions, open 1 June-10 Sept) the route climbs through intact seter country in Sølendalen, sheep and cattle grazing among working summer farms, tops out at about 1,270 m near km 111, then drops roughly 1,000 vertical metres off Storlegda into the Rendalen valley, the leg's low point at about 265 m near km 124. Rendalen markets itself on exactly these mountain gravel roads. The route passes within ~3 km of Bergset, Rendalen's municipal centre with two grocery shops (worth the detour for resupply); Otnes and the Jacob Breda Bull museum lie further south and are skippable. From the valley floor the route stays east of the Glomma and climbs directly over to Jutulhogget on Jutulhoggveien, joining the Glomma valley (Rv3) only after the canyon at km ~141. [Detour: On route, km 74-130 | Near: Rendalen]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.2934,62.0258,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Nordistusetra i Sølendalen</name><description>A genuinely working dairy seter in Nordre Sølendalen that hosts visitors: dairy cows and calves on site, a simple guest cabin, traditional fare (milk cakes, coffee, smoked whitefish), fishing and paddling on the Sølna. The family is on the seter from around midsummer to early August, which matches a ~11-12 July pass-through. It sits down in the valley about 5.4 km off the high route near track km 97. Call ahead (+47 995 60 171) to confirm they are receiving visitors before committing to the detour; this is a working farm, not a cafe with posted hours. [Detour: About 5-6 km each way off route at km ~97, on valley seter roads; call ahead | Near: Rendalen]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.4997,62.02241,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Jutulhogget canyon</name><description>Billed by researchers as northern Europe's largest canyon (local sources say one of its longest), and the headline stop of the leg: 2.4 km long with walls up to 240 m. Carved in days, not millennia, by a catastrophic outburst flood of up to 180,000 m3/s when the ice dam of glacial lake Nedre Glomsjø (surface four times today's Mjøsa, volume close to Sweden's Vänern) collapsed roughly 10,400 years ago; a nature reserve since 1959 and one of the First 100 IUGS geological heritage sites. Geometry verified against the GPX: the route runs directly past the rim viewpoint at track km 140.5, on the climb out of Rendalen before the descent to the Glomma valley and Alvdal, so this is a zero-detour stop. Budget 20-30 min at the rim; a path leads partway into the canyon if legs allow. [Detour: None: the track passes the rim viewpoint at km 140.5 | Near: Alvdal]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>10.88802,61.99772,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Tronfjell (Tron, 1,666 m) via Tronfjellveien</name><description>Free-standing massif towering over Alvdal with a gravel road (built in one month in 1959 for the NRK transmitter) climbing to near the summit, widely billed as Norway's second-highest road and a known strength-test climb: about 11 km and 1,160 vertical metres from the Alvdal side at around 10% average. Electronic card toll above Tronsvangen setergrend applies to cars; cyclists ride free. The summit panorama is said to take in seven parishes; the Flattron plateau halfway up carries the story of Indian philosopher Sri Ananda Acharya (Baral), who lived 28 years here (1917-1945) dreaming of a Peace University, and lies buried at about 1,400 m. Honest verdict: from Alvdal (about 480 m) this is a half-day side trip on loaded legs; only for riders banking spare hours at the Alvdal stop or taking a rest day. [Detour: Side trip from Alvdal (track km 163): roughly 11-13 km and ~1,160 m climbing each way on the gravel toll road (free for bikes) | Near: Alvdal]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>10.689,62.1715,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Aukrustsenteret (Huset Aukrust), Alvdal</name><description>Museum for Kjell Aukrust, Alvdal's own author-cartoonist behind Flåklypa Grand Prix (the most-watched Norwegian film ever), in a long, low landmark building by Pritzker laureate Sverre Fehn. Artist museum NOK 185 adult; museum shop and the Solan og Ludvig cafe are free to enter, and the Flåklypatoppen moon rocket (La Pollo XIII) runs daily in the school summer holidays from 22 June (NOK 75 supplement, 8 per tour). Open daily 10:00-16:00 in summer. Geometry verified: it sits about 100 m off the track at km 163.6, right where the leg ends, so even a cafe-and-shop stop is effectively free. Good end-of-leg morale stop before the climb out of Alvdal. [Detour: None: about 100 m off route at km 163.6 in Alvdal | Near: Alvdal]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>10.6219,62.1136,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Huset Aukrust (Aukrustsenteret)</name><description>Museum in Alvdal dedicated to author and illustrator Kjell Aukrust (creator of Flaklypa), housed in a striking long building by Pritzker Prize architect Sverre Fehn; opened 1996 as Aukrustsenteret, renamed Huset Aukrust in 2019. Holds Aukrust's drawings and a model of the Il Tempo Gigante car. A short culture stop before the route climbs out of Osterdalen, useful if you are resupplying in Alvdal anyway. [Detour: In Alvdal at track km 163, under 1 km off route | Near: Alvdal]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>10.6219,62.1136,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Grimsdalen protected landscape and Grimsdalsvegen toll road</name><description>Roughly 40 km gravel mountain road through what Norwegians market as 'the world's most beautiful seter valley', a protected landscape (landskapsvernomrade) between Rondane and Dovrefjell. Used for livestock and seter traffic since the 1600s; the valley holds working summer farm clusters (Tollevshaugen is the largest with 11 seters; Verkensetrene with the old Pondervangen trading site), Viking-age graves (one near the Mesaetre road dated to ~900) and large reindeer mass-trapping systems. Automated toll for motor vehicles (plate camera via youpark.no), nothing to pay on a bike; officially open about 5 June to 1 December, with sections occasionally night-closed for wild reindeer. The track rides its full length, entering from the Folldal side. [Detour: On route, approx km 190-245 | Near: Grimsdalshytta]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.826,62.0904,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Grimsdalshytta (DNT) with Rondane panorama</name><description>Historic DNT Oslo og Omegn lodge mid-valley with what ut.no calls an incredibly beautiful view toward Rondane's majestic peaks across the valley. 54 beds plus a 19-bed self-service annex; staffed with food service from roughly mid-June to mid-September (self-service rest of year outside reindeer calving season). The natural overnight or lunch stop in Grimsdalen at ~km 230. [Detour: On route, km ~230 | Near: Grimsdalshytta]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.6422,62.0911,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Vegaskillet rest area (Grimsdalsvegen/Haverdalsvegen fork)</name><description>Rest stop at the road fork on the western section of Grimsdalsvegen where the side road to Haverdalseter branches off (vegaskillet means 'the road divide', not a watershed). Benches, a couple of small lakes and fishing water make it a documented break spot, about 6 km up from the Eftansae toll point on the Dovre side; you pass it on the long descent toward Dovre/Gudbrandsdalen. Note: the viewpoint name 'Gravbekkleitet' from older route notes could not be verified; Vegaskillet is the documented stop. [Detour: On route | Near: Grimsdalshytta]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.4181,62.0276,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Rondane National Park (northern edge)</name><description>Norway's first national park (1962), home to wild reindeer and the iconic 2178 m Rondslottet. The route does not enter the park but rides its northern boundary through Grimsdalen, with constant views of the peaks; cycling inside the park is restricted to designated routes. Marked DNT trails into the park (e.g. toward Doralseter) start at Grimsdalshytta if you want a foot detour. [Detour: Views on route; entering the park requires a hike from Grimsdalshytta | Near: Grimsdalshytta]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.7966,61.8876,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Musk ox safari, Dovrefjell (Hjerkinn/Dombas)</name><description>Dovrefjell holds Norway's only wild musk ox herd, one of very few in Europe and by far the easiest to reach. Guided safaris meet at Hjerkinn at 09:45 for a 10:00 start and walk 7-15 km over roughly 3-7 hours (typically ~6) depending on where the herd is. Not on the route: Hjerkinn is ~30 km northeast of Dombas up the E6, but it is one train stop away (four daily trains each direction on the Dovre line), so the practical option is a half-rest-day from Dombas (km 264). Book ahead for a July Saturday. [Detour: Off route: ~30 km each way from Dombas, or one train stop to Hjerkinn; plan a half day | Near: Dombas]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.55,62.2231,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Fokstumyra Nature Reserve</name><description>Norway's first nature reserve (protected 1923) and a Ramsar wetland (2002) on the Dovrefjell plateau: ~7.5 km2 of marsh with ~170 recorded bird species including bluethroat, common crane, hen harrier, ruff and short-eared owl. A 7 km loop trail, partly boardwalk, is the only permitted way through the reserve, so it costs real time. Worthwhile mainly for birders; others get better value staying on the route. [Detour: Off route: ~11 km north of Dombas on the busy E6 each way, plus the 7 km walking loop | Near: Dombas]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.2827,62.1366,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Sladalsvegen high mountain road</name><description>32 km summer-only toll gravel road (toll for motor vehicles only; normally opens the first Monday after 17 May) from Lesja over the plateau to Vagamo, topping out at 1180 m on an old seter and livestock track. From the open plateau you see mountains in five national parks: Dovrefjell-Sunndalsfjella (Snohetta), Dovre, Rondane, Jotunheimen and Reinheimen, followed by a long descent into Vaga. This is the route's marquee gravel sector between Dombas and Vaga (roughly km 280-310). Essentially no services on top (at most a seter serving simple food in season); carry water. [Detour: On route, summit roughly km 295 | Near: Vaga]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.0061,61.9716,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Vagakyrkja (Vaga Church)</name><description>One of Norway's oldest wooden churches: originally a stave church from ~1150, rebuilt 1625-27 as a cruciform church reusing the medieval materials, including carved stave-church portals and decorative wall planks. Inside are an early-Gothic crucifix from the mid-1200s, a pulpit from ~1630 and a 1674 altarpiece. Right in Vagamo centre at km 311, a 15-minute stop alongside resupply. [Detour: On route in Vagamo centre | Near: Vaga]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.0977,61.8759,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Jutulporten rock gate</name><description>A ~25 m high rock face just above Vagamo where the light-coloured stone forms what looks like an arched gateway into the mountain, home of the jutul (mountain troll) in the tale of Jutuln and Johannes Blessom recorded by Asbjornsen. Reached by turning off at the church and following the road ~800 m, then bearing right and left toward Ovre Nordherad for a few hundred metres more. Quick, free and pairs naturally with the church and museum. [Detour: ~1-2 km off route from Vagamo centre plus a short walk | Near: Vaga]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.0866,61.8761,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Jutulheimen bygdamuseum</name><description>Vaga's small open-air folk museum near Jutulporten, with historic log buildings and exhibitions on reindeer-hunting legend Jo Gjende and woodcarver Jo Visdal. Important caveat: in summer the buildings and exhibitions are shown by appointment only (arrange via Gudbrandsdalsmusea), so it is not a drop-in stop; contact ahead if you want a tour. [Detour: On route in Vagamo, ~500 m from centre | Near: Vaga]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.0858,61.8747,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Klones historic farm estate</name><description>Farm estate on Vagavatnet documented since the 1500s; the great Storofsen flood of July 1789 destroyed about half the farm's assets. English gentleman-explorer Eardley John Blackwell (who came around 1850 with Theodore Rathbone to explore Jotunheimen, befriending hunter Jo Gjende) bought Klones in 1859 and built the grand English manor-style main house in 1867-73. An agricultural school for ~90 years (1919-2009); today it offers rooms, apartments, breakfast and dining. A practical sleep option ~2 km south of Vagamo on Rv15, essentially on the route toward Randsverk. [Detour: On or immediately beside the route, ~2 km south of Vagamo | Near: Vaga]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.0834,61.8616,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Ridderspranget gorge (Sjoa river)</name><description>Dramatic slot gorge where the glacier-green Sjoa river is squeezed between rock walls, named for the medieval legend of the knight Sigvat from Valdres leaping the chasm with the bride he had stolen from Ivar Gjesling of Sandbu. The side road leaves Rv51 5 km south of Randsverk, runs ~1 km to a parking area with picnic tables and toilets, then a 250 m walk to the edge. If the GPX turns off Rv51 into Murudalen at Randsverk, this is roughly a 12 km round-trip detour; verify the exact turn against the track. Do not attempt the jump. [Detour: ~12 km round trip from the Randsverk junction plus 250 m walk (verify against GPX) | Near: Vaga]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.0754,61.6822,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Jotunheimvegen / Vinstre plateau panorama</name><description>The 45 km summer-only toll gravel road (toll for motor vehicles; open roughly late June until the snow comes in October, so confirm status if riding early season) between Skabu and Rv51 near Bygdin crosses an open mountain plateau and follows the north shores of Sandvatnet and Vinstri (Vinstre), with big-sky views to the Jotunheimen peaks, possible sightings of the local herding cooperative's reindeer, and small mountain farms along the lake. This is the scenic payoff of the Murudalen-Vinstre leg (roughly km 370-414). Note: the Besseggen ridge itself is not visible from here; its trailhead at Gjendesheim lies ~25-30 km off route via Rv51 from Randsverk and is a full-day hike, not realistic mid-tour. [Detour: On route along Vinstre's north shore (coordinates approximate) | Near: Haugseter]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.88,61.34,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Haugseter Fjellstue</name><description>Mountain lodge with 140 years of history on the north shore of Vinstre at ~km 385, the only real services on the plateau stretch between Murudalen and Bygdin: 8 apartments and 6 cabins (~74 beds), a kitchen known for traditional Norwegian food (sour cream porridge, local trout, reindeer stew), plus boat rental and fishing. Open from 19 June through September, so fine for mid-July. Useful planned stop for the night of day 3-4. [Detour: On route, km ~385 | Near: Haugseter]</description><styleUrl>#s0</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.984,61.3424,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
</Folder>
<Folder><name>Eat &amp; drink</name>
<Placemark><name>Heimatt Bakeri &amp; Restaurant</name><description>bakery: The village bakery, run by two brothers from a local Beitostolen farm who also run the 10-seat farm-to-table 'Heilt Heimatt' tasting restaurant and Heimatt catering (ranked #3 in town on TripAdvisor). Cinnamon buns get rave reviews, some call them the best in Norway. Bygdinvegen 3782, mid-village (in the Bergo building area). Bakery operates in summer but with a smaller range than winter; restaurant runs Wed-Sat and books out. Bakery hours are short and posted on their Facebook page, so check before relying on it for breakfast. [Bakery items NOK 40-90; restaurant dinner NOK 600+]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.9074,61.2481,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Cafeen Tapasbar</name><description>cafe: Cozy cafe-bar 'full of soul' on the main drag (Bygdinvegen 3802): bistro dishes, sharing plates and tapas, homemade focus. Good relaxed dinner for two riders. Hours verified: Mon-Thu 15:00-22:00, Fri-Sat 12:00-23:00, CLOSED Sundays; kitchen until 22:00. Sister wine bar Chambre by Cafeen next door. [Mains/tapas NOK 150-300]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.9052,61.2487,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Bryggerihuset Beitostolen</name><description>pub: Highest-rated spot in town (TripAdvisor; Yelp listing updated May 2026): brewpub at Bygdinvegen 3776 with the widest beer selection in Beitostolen, gastropub food, and outdoor summer grilling. Note it sits ~200 m SE of the SPAR/roundabout cluster, on the lower stretch of Bygdinvegen. The obvious post-ride beer stop. Verify summer opening days on their Facebook/Instagram; it leans weekend-heavy outside ski season. Tel +47 924 48 646. [Beer NOK 100-140, pub food NOK 200-350]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.9096,61.2471,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Jotunstogo</name><description>restaurant: Traditional Norwegian cafe-restaurant-winebar by the Rv51 roundabout (Bygdinvegen 3783, next to SPAR), known for its Today's Special, generous portions, fast service and mountain views; they will wrap leftovers to take away. Open daily 10:00-18:00 (Sun 11:00-18:00), so it works for breakfast, lunch or an early dinner, and is one of the few places serving on Sundays. Closes 18:00, so eat early. [~NOK 200-300 per person]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.907,61.2487,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Café Gjendeosen</name><description>cafe: Café at the Gjende boat pier, 200m from the DNT lodge. Freshly baked waffles, cinnamon buns and bread, plus warm dishes, ice cream and snacks. Opens one hour before the first Gjendebåten departure and closes an hour after the last boat: 06:45-21:00 in July high season, seven days a week, so the Sunday problem does not apply here. [Waffles/buns ~50-90 NOK, light meals ~100-200 NOK (estimate; no published price list)]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.8092,61.4954,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Gjendesheim Turisthytte (DNT dinner)</name><description>mountain_lodge: The big staffed DNT lodge at the foot of Besseggen serves a proper three-course dinner built on local produce, with summer sittings at 19:00 and 21:00, plus breakfast. The best post-ride dinner at the stop itself. Note: DNT staffed lodges do not allow eating your own food or using stoves on the premises (confirmed in 2026 price list). Open daily through July; summer season runs roughly early/mid-June to early October. [3-course dinner 470 NOK member / 608 NOK non-member; breakfast 190/253 NOK (official 2026 DNT Oslo og Omegn prices)]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.8126,61.4943,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Bessheim Fjellstue restaurant</name><description>mountain_lodge: Family-run mountain lodge about 5 km north of Gjendesheim down Sjodalen (paved Fv51, easy spin). Well regarded kitchen: three-course dinner served daily through the summer season (5 June to 20 September in 2026), mountain trout a speciality. Open daily in July including Sundays. Dinner must be reserved by the day before: phone +47 61 23 89 13 or post@bessheim.no. [3-course dinner ~570 NOK (2025 reference; 2026 not published); breakfast ~210 NOK]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.853,61.5146,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Vasetstølen</name><description>mountain_lodge: Historic stølsgard (summer-farm courtyard, 1700s/1800s log buildings) serving the best traditional food at Vaset: rømmegrøt is the signature (up to 50L served daily, order it with cured meats like the locals), plus majel soup, mountain trout, local lamb and game. Season runs 1 June to 10 Oct. Summer serving hours confirmed on the official site (June 2026): Tue-Thu 12:00-16:00, Fri-Sat 12:00-17:00, Sun 12:00-18:00, closed Mondays. Open Sunday 12 July. Cyclist-friendly, listed Mjølkevegen partner. Note: occasionally closes for private events (e.g. confirmations), so a quick call (+47 61 36 33 50) the day before is cheap insurance. [Rømmegrøt/mains roughly 150-300 NOK]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.9774,60.9934,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Sekskanten Kro og Pub</name><description>pub: The post-ride dinner option at Vaset centre: hexagonal kro/pub with daily a la carte, dish of the day, burgers, and traditional Valdres dishes (rømmegrøt, majel). Dine in or takeaway. Hours confirmed on official site (June 2026): Mon-Fri 11:00-17:00, Sat 12:00-19:00, Sun 12:00-17:00, so eat early; kitchen closes by 17:00 most days. No seasonal closure listed. Confirmed operating (sekskanten.no, +47 61 34 47 00 / 415 08 415). [Mains ~200-350 NOK]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.9853,60.9954,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Langestølen Café and Store (Langestølen Kolonial og Kafé)</name><description>cafe: Traditional café and convenience store (landhandel) directly on the Mjølkevegen at the north end of Tisleifjorden, about 13 km south of Vaset on the Vaset-Golsfjellet stage. Address Tisleivegen 1680, 2918 Ulnes. Listed Mjølkevegen partner: food, drinks, small shop for top-up supplies, e-bike charging. Open winter holiday, Easter and roughly four summer months, so mid-July falls in season, but hours are seasonal and not published; aim for late morning to mid-afternoon and carry backup snacks in case it is shut. [Waffles/coffee 50-120 NOK]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.9415,60.8766,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Gol Bakeri og Konditori</name><description>bakery: Traditional Hallingdal bakery with two outlets in town (main at Sentrumsvegen 11, branch at Sentrumsvegen 114). Old-school methods, big counter of fresh bread, cakes, buns and ice cream; lots of seating, ~80 seats at the main outlet. The obvious morning stop before rolling out toward Geilo. Hours (verified on golbakeri.no): main Mon-Fri 09:00-16:00, Sat 09:00-15:00; branch Mon-Fri 09:00-17:00, Sat 09:00-16:00. BOTH CLOSED SUNDAYS, so no bakery breakfast on 12 July. [Coffee + bun ~60-90 NOK]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.96685,60.70145,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Kjersti's Mat og Vinhus</name><description>restaurant: The best sit-down food in Gol centre (Sentrumsvegen 65). Cafe by day (soups, sandwiches, salads, cakes baked in-house daily), a la carte in the evening with a dry-aging cabinet for steaks; summer terrace. Tripadvisor 3.8/5, #2 of 17 in Gol; reviews praise the dry-aged entrecote, some find portions small for the price. WARNING: listed hours are Mon-Thu 11:00-20:00, Fri-Sat 11:00-22:00, i.e. CLOSED SUNDAYS. Do not plan on it for a Sunday 12 July dinner; call +47 954 84 216 to check for summer exceptions. [Mains ~250-450 NOK]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.94976,60.70129,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Erik's Grill &amp; Sportsbar (Pers Hotell)</name><description>pub: Informal grill and sports bar inside the Pers Hotell complex, Sentrumsvegen 72 (some listings give Dalevegen 1, same building block). Burgers including an Impossible Burger, a la carte grill menu, beer on tap, Premier League and F1 on screens, piano bar with live music on weekends. Best bet for a post-ride dinner on a Sunday evening when much else in Gol is shut (hotel kitchen, but exact Sunday hours not published; the hotel's main restaurant serves dinner daily as fallback). Note: bar and grill have a 20+ age minimum, children only when accompanying adults. [Burgers/mains ~200-350 NOK]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.94812,60.70057,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Bistro at First Camp Gol - Hallingdal</name><description>restaurant: On-site bistro at the First Camp campsite (Heradvegen 189), indoor and outdoor seating, rustic simple meals from snacks to spareribs and plaice, beer and wine. Open during reception hours (typically 08:00-19:00 outside peak weeks), so plan an early dinner. Only worth it if you sleep at First Camp; saves the 3 km ride back into the centre. Site and bistro confirmed operating for the summer 2026 season. [Mains ~180-300 NOK]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.00517,60.69986,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Haugastol Turistsenter cafe &amp; restaurant</name><description>restaurant: The hub at the start of Rallarvegen and effectively the only food at Haugastol itself: coffee bar, restaurant and bike shop in one family-run complex by the station. Tripadvisor reviewers rate the food among the best they've had in Norway: fresh meat dishes, good salad/veg choices, praised pizza and a big spread of homemade cakes. Restaurant serves breakfast, lunch and dinner mid-June to mid-October; in the 1 July-9 August window breakfast is 08:00-10:00 and dinner is served daily at 19:00, Sundays included, so mid-July is fully covered. Dinner ~390 NOK, breakfast ~175 NOK (approximate; exact prices only shown in booking flow). [Dinner ~390 NOK, breakfast ~175 NOK (approximate)]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.8531,60.5124,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Fagerheim Fjellstugu cafe</name><description>mountain_lodge: Staffed mountain lodge on Rv7 southwest of Haugastol (9 km direct, ~12 km by road) on the edge of Hardangervidda with views toward the Hardangerjokulen glacier. Cafe open 11:00-18:00 every day, year-round (confirmed on the lodge's own site and ut.no), plus a set three-course dinner served 19:00. A worthwhile detour ride for dinner if Haugastol's restaurant is full, or a meal stop if you camp on the plateau nearby. Note: no consuming your own food on the premises. [Three-course dinner included for overnight guests; cafe a la carte]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.7852,60.4396,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Oksebotn rallarcafe (vokterbolig)</name><description>cafe: Historic 1913 railway guard's house ~19 km along Rallarvegen toward Finse (8 km before Finse), at ~1,150 m. Tiny privately run summer cafe famous for homemade hot waffles: longtime waffle-maker Eivind Haukvik turns out 120-150 waffle plates a day on busy weekends. Normally opens daily from mid-July (snow-dependent) until Norwegian school start, hours sporadic. Perfect mid-ride stop on your Haugastol-Finse leg, but with a mid-July trip you may arrive days before it opens for the season: carry food. [Waffles/coffee ~50-100 NOK]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.5969,60.5592,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Finsehytta cafe &amp; restaurant (DNT)</name><description>mountain_lodge: DNT's big staffed lodge on the south shore of Finsevatnet, 300m from the station. Daytime cafe does Norwegian waffles, cakes, pizza and lighter hot meals; evenings a proper 3-course dinner. Home of Finse 1223, Norway's highest microbrewery (in the cellar), with their own pilsner, pale ale and cider on tap. Open to non-residents, daily through the summer season; 2026 summer season opens 26 June, so fully open mid-July. Renovated and expanded in recent years. [Waffles/cake ~60-100 NOK, pizza ~200 NOK, 3-course dinner ~545 NOK (DNT price list dated 2023, expect modest increases)]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.507,60.5979,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Hotel Finse 1222 restaurant &amp; bar</name><description>restaurant: Historic railway hotel right on the platform. Restaurant does locally sourced 3-course dinners (rotating set menu) with glacier views, plus a bar/lounge for a post-ride beer. Lunch (homemade pizza, reindeer burger, Rallarsuppe) is served daily but must be booked in advance. Open to non-residents. Summer season covers mid-July, and from 2026 the hotel runs year-round. [3-course dinner roughly 600-700 NOK; bar prices typical Norwegian mountain hotel]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.5031,60.6018,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Fagernut Vokterbolig cafe (Rallarvaffel stop)</name><description>cafe: Stone track-watchman's cottage from 1904 at 1,310m, 9km west of Finse directly on Rallarvegen, run by the Navvy Museum. THE classic stop on the Finse-Myrdal leg: waffles, coffee and navvy soup. CAUTION on dates: opens daily 10:00-16:30 from roughly MID-July (exact date varies with snow clearing) until school start, then weekends to late September. On a 14-16 July ride it may have just opened or not yet; check the Rallarvegen report and do not rely on it for calories. Cash in NOK or Vipps; card not always accepted. [Waffle + coffee ~70-100 NOK]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.3766,60.6243,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Flam Bakeri</name><description>bakery: Artisan bakery on the quay, steps from the Flamsbana station. Fresh skillingsboller (Norwegian cinnamon buns), bread baked through the day, sandwiches, pastries and Italian-style pizzas. Open every day year-round 08:00-17:00, so it works even on a Sunday. The obvious first stop after rolling off the Rallarvegen descent. [Buns ~NOK 45-60, sandwiches ~NOK 100-150]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.1128,60.8628,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Aegir Gastropub (Flamsbrygga, formerly Aegir BrewPub)</name><description>pub: Stave-church-styled brewpub on the harbourfront, long-running Tripadvisor #1 in Flam and multiple-time Norway BrewPub of the Year. The Jan 2026 renovation is complete: it reopened rebranded as Aegir Gastropub, one of three dining concepts at Flamsbrygga (alongside Fjord Bistro and Flam Restaurant). Viking-inspired menu with local beer pairings (the Viking Plank concept). Confirmed operating through summer 2026. Book a table in July. [Mains ~NOK 250-400, Viking Plank/beer-pairing menu ~NOK 600+]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.114,60.8636,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Restaurant Arven (Fretheim Hotel)</name><description>restaurant: The dining room of the historic Fretheim Hotel, 2nd floor: locally sourced fjord and farm ingredients, modern Norwegian cooking. High-season (May-Sept) evening buffet with fish, shellfish, local meats and desserts, around NOK 695 per person in recent reviews (expect a modest increase for 2026). The best 'proper' dinner in the village if you want to celebrate finishing the route. Reserve ahead in mid-July. [Dinner buffet ~NOK 695 pp (recent seasons)]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.113,60.8612,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Fjord Bistro (formerly Furukroa Kafe)</name><description>cafe: Casual bistro-cafe in the harbour courtyard at Flamsbrygga, rebranded from Furukroa Kafe in the 2026 renovation. Lunch, dinner, barista coffee and cakes through the day; menu has included the Flam Burger, Aegir-beer-battered fish and chips, soup and pizzas, plus a summer ice cream counter. Big harbour-view terrace. The cheap-and-fast option when the bakery queue is long; busiest when cruise ships and trains coincide. Showing FIFA World Cup 2026 matches, so confirmed open in summer 2026. [Mains ~NOK 150-250]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.1137,60.8634,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Trygstad Bakeri og Konditori</name><description>bakery: The classic Roros bakery at Kjerkgata 12, baking since 1906 (not 1948 as often misquoted; official site: 'siden 1906'). Famous for skoleboller and solboller; ideal pre-departure carb load and pastries to pack for the first leg toward Gradalen. Open Mon-Fri 08:30-17:00, Sat 09:00-16:00, and (unusually for Norway) Sunday 11:30-16:30 thanks to Roros' tourist-town status. [30-60 NOK per pastry]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.3851,62.5753,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Kaffestuggu</name><description>cafe: Roros' oldest eating house (Bergmannsgata 18), cafe-restaurant doing local produce with a modern twist: open sandwiches, sodd, reindeer dishes, good cakes and coffee. Open daily including Sundays (Mon-Wed and Sun 11:00-18:00, Thu-Sat 11:00-23:00). Reliable lunch or early dinner. [Mains ~200-350 NOK]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.386,62.5752,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Vertshuset Roros</name><description>restaurant: The best dinner in town: historic inn at Kjerkgata 34 serving regional Roros food (reindeer, local lamb, Rorosmeieriet dairy). Restaurant open Tue 17:00-23:00, Wed-Sat 12:00-16:00 and 17:00-23:00 (kitchen closes 21:30). Closed Sun-Mon, so fine for a Wed/Thu start night. Hours and operation confirmed on the official Roroshotellene page; booking engine live for summer 2026. [Mains ~300-450 NOK]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.3867,62.5763,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Skanckebua</name><description>pub: Gastropub mid-way up Kjerkgata, run by Bergstadens Hotel, with an upstairs bar overlooking the street. Local meat and fish, burgers (the reindeer burger is a top seller), fish and chips, tacos; no pizza. Open Tue-Thu 12:00-23:00, Fri-Sat 12:00-02:00 (kitchen to 22:00); closed Sun-Mon, so time your pint for Tue-Sat. Confirmed operating via Bergstadens Hotel and Visit Roros. [Mains ~200-450 NOK]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.3862,62.5759,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Ellefsplass provisions room (DNT matlager)</name><description>mountain_lodge: The hut itself is dinner: self-service DNT cabin with a stocked provisions room (tinned/dried meals, breakfast staples) plus full kitchen, electricity and running water. No staffed meals or meal times; you cook, then register and pay food in the DNT app. Open 1 Jun-10 Sep, so mid-July is fine. Non-guests may buy food without paying the day-visit fee (confirmed in the 2026 price list: payment only required if you also use the common room or kitchen). [Pantry items at DNT list prices, pay in app]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.44822,62.20446,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Jonasvollen Camping kiosk (Femundsenden)</name><description>cafe: Lakeside kiosk at the south end of Lake Femunden, departure point for the MS Faemund II boat. Kiosk sales, fishing licences, boat hire and marina. Only worth it as a roughly 9-12 km detour east/southeast from Tufsingdal village for a snack stop and a look at Femunden; it is the only place resembling a cafe anywhere near this leg. The site itself is open year-round per jonasvollen.no, but kiosk hours vary, so call +47 414 03 216 or +47 62 49 89 94 before detouring. [Kiosk prices]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.874,62.232,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Frich's Spiseri Alvdal</name><description>restaurant: Roadside diner-restaurant on Rv3 at Nord-Østerdalsveien 5148, Steimosletta, next to Aukrustsenteret. Verified hours: cafe 08:00-23:00 daily, breakfast 07:00-10:00, dagens middag 12:00-20:00 (Sat to 19:00), a la carte to 21:30 (Sat 20:30). The reliable hot-meal option in Alvdal and open Sundays, unlike most of the town. Phone +47 62 48 80 00. [Mains ~NOK 200-330]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>10.6174,62.1144,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Huldra kafe (Huldra handverk, mat og kultur)</name><description>cafe: Craft shop and cafe at Steia 10 in Alvdal centre, confirmed operating: fresh yeast bakes, cakes, open sandwiches, simple hot dishes and popular soups. Daytime hours only (roughly 10:00-16:00, check their Facebook page) and closed Sundays, so it works for a Friday/Saturday arrival but not Sunday 12 July. [Coffee + cake ~NOK 100-150, soup lunch ~NOK 150]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>10.6329,62.1082,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Solan og Ludvigs kafe at Aukrustsenteret</name><description>cafe: Cafe inside the Kjell Aukrust centre on Steimosletta, a few hundred metres from Frich's. Verified open daily 10:00-18:00 in July, including Sundays. Light meals, cake and coffee; combine with the Flaklypa exhibit if you have a rest hour. [Light meals ~NOK 100-200]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>10.6219,62.1136,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Grimsdalshytta dining room (DNT staffed hut)</name><description>mountain_lodge: The hut itself is the food stop: staffed summer season confirmed 19 Jun-13 Sep 2026 on the DNT English page, so open Sunday 12 July. Three-course dinner served at 19:00 every day (tell the warden on arrival; non-residents and tenters can eat if there is space). Day service 12:00-16:00 confirmed: soup, blings, roemmevafler (sour-cream waffles) and cakes, plus drinks and kiosk items; the hut also does stone-oven-baked pizza. All food made from scratch with local ingredients. Breakfast 190 NOK member / 253 non-member. Note DNT rule (verbatim in the 2026 price sheet): no eating your own food inside the hut, and own stoves cannot be used at the hut even outdoors. [Dinner 470 NOK member / 608 non-member; plate dish 258/300; waffles+coffee ~100]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.6418,62.0912,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Grimsbu Turistsenter kafeteria</name><description>cafe: Roadside cafeteria at the eastern toll gate of Grimsdalsvegen (route km ~205, the last services before the 25 km climb to the hut). Open year-round; posted hours Mon-Fri 08:00-22:00, Sat-Sun 09:00-19:00 (so open Sunday 12 July, confirm on the day). On-site supermarket/kiosk and guest kitchen too. Honest truck-stop style rather than destination food, but reliable hot meals and the only kitchen between Alvdal and the hut. Phone +47 62 49 35 29. [Cafeteria mains ~150-250 NOK]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>10.1714,62.1554,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Toftemo Turiststasjon cafe</name><description>cafe: Next-morning option on the descent to Dombaas: classic tourist station on the E6 at Vestsidevegen 1, Dovre, about 2 km north of Dovre village and ~9.5 km south of Dombaas (route km ~255). Cafeteria seats 75, a la carte menu plus breakfast/lunch service, homemade food. Good first coffee after rolling out of Grimsdalen. Phone +47 61 24 00 45 to confirm morning hours. [Mains ~180-280 NOK, coffee and waffles less]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.221,61.9995,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Bokhandel'n Bakeri &amp; Mathus (Gjestehus)</name><description>bakery: The standout food stop in Vagamo: stone-oven bakery, pizza, burgers and pulled-pork sandwiches in a historic timber bookshop at Vagavegen 45 on the village square, run with Classic Norway Hotels as Bokhandel'n Gjestehus. Google 4.2 (396 reviews), verified. Current listed hours verified: Fri-Sat 10:00-22:00, Sun 12:00-20:00, Mon-Tue 10:00-17:00, Wed-Thu closed (likely extends to daily in peak July, but do not count on Wed-Thu). Confirmed OPEN Sunday, so this is your Sunday 12 July dinner plan. 700 m from Smedsmo Camping. [Pizza/mains ~200-300 NOK]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.0941,61.8751,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Cafe Edvard at Ullinsvin</name><description>cafe: Summer cafe in the old vicarage (Edvard Munch family connection) above Vaga church, with gallery, historic garden and local-food shop, good for coffee, home baking and snacks. 2026 season verified on ullinsvin.no: Cafe Edvard opens 20 June 2026, summer exhibitions run 21 June to 7 September and are open daily, so it works for a Sunday 12 July lunch. Typical hours 11:00-17:00 (exact 2026 daily hours not yet published, confirm on arrival). 10 min walk uphill from the centre. [Coffee and cake ~100-150 NOK]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.09,61.8773,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Villa Vaga restaurant</name><description>restaurant: Restaurant of the village hotel (Classic Norway Hotels), in the centre. Official site confirms a la carte menu in the summer season (the buffet/set-dish service is winter, for hotel guests). The reliable sit-down dinner if Bokhandel'n is full; non-guest dining not explicitly stated, call ahead (+47 99 49 25 35). Operating 2026. [Dinner ~250-400 NOK]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.0958,61.8746,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Isbaren i Vaga</name><description>cafe: Ice-cream and small-dishes bar at Moavegen 1 in the village centre, dine-in and outdoor seating, active Facebook presence. Seasonal; July daily hours unverified, check Facebook. Backup if closed Sunday: Visit Vaga isbar/Vagais at Vagavegen 51A, a combined tourist office, ice-cream bar (local Vagais factory) and bakery outlet. [Ice cream/small dishes 60-180 NOK]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.0948,61.8752,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Haugseter Fjellstue restaurant</name><description>mountain_lodge: The lodge itself is the only food at this stop and it is genuinely good: kitchen built on game, trout from Vinstervatn (the house speciality), local cured meats and stolslapper (mountain pancakes) with jam. Open every day in season (19 June to 27 Sept 2026, confirmed on haugseter.no), restaurant 11:00-20:00, lunch from 11:00, dinner menu 15:00-20:00; call ahead for table reservations. Drop-in travellers welcome (it is the classic road stop on Jotunheimvegen / Mjolkevegen cycle route). Open Sundays, so 12 July is no problem. Breakfast 220 NOK, packed lunch 85 NOK. Generator off 23:00-07:00. [Breakfast 220 NOK, packed lunch 85 NOK (both confirmed); dinner mains not published, budget ~250-400 NOK]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.984,61.3424,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Bygdin sommerkafe (Bygdin Hoifieldshotel)</name><description>cafe: Next food on the route, about 11 km past Haugseter where Jotunheimvegen meets Rv51 at the east end of lake Bygdin (NOT 29 km: Haugseter's own site puts it 24 km from Beitostolen, and Bygdin sits 13 km from Beitostolen between them). Summer cafe open 12 June through the first week of October, daily 11:00-18:00: waffles, rommegrot, daily soup, hot and cold dishes and daily dinner plates (children's menu too). Hotel restaurant serves 3-course dinners in the evening (book). Good morning-coffee target if you sleep at Haugseter. [Cafe prices not published; ~100-150 NOK waffles/soup, ~200-300 NOK hot dishes is a reasonable budget]</description><styleUrl>#s1</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.8011,61.3276,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
</Folder>
<Folder><name>Resupply (groceries)</name>
<Placemark><name>SPAR Beitostolen</name><description>grocery: Main resupply: full supermarket at Bygdinvegen 3783 with fresh bakery, produce, hot/cold deli counter, in-store Vitusapotek pharmacy and Post i Butikk. Open Mon-Sat 08:00-22:00 and, unusually for Norway, SUNDAYS 09:00-20:00 (tourist-resort exemption, verified). Backup options in town: KIWI at Ovrevegen 4A (closed Sundays) and Coop Extra at Stolstunet, Bygdinvegen 3762. Last proper supermarket before the Slettefjell climb to Vaset. [Normal Norwegian supermarket prices]</description><styleUrl>#s2</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.9071,61.2486,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Kiwi 243 Beitostølen</name><description>grocery: There is no grocery store at Gjendesheim or anywhere in Sjodalen; this Kiwi in Beitostølen (Øvrevegen 4A) is the resupply point before riding north over Valdresflye, about 28-30 km south. Crucially it is open Sundays 09:00-21:00 (tourist-area exemption), so a Sunday passage still works. Stock up fully here: next reliable shops are in Vågå or back in Beitostølen. [Standard Kiwi supermarket prices]</description><styleUrl>#s2</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.9209,61.2429,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Joker Vaset (Vasetsenteret)</name><description>grocery: Main resupply for this leg and an unusually good one: named store of the year in the Joker chain (award covered by Avisa Valdres), stocks local seasonal produce plus hardware/sports goods, and is a confirmed sales outlet for Bakeriet i Valdres (Bakeriet i Bagn) baked goods. Critically, it is OPEN SUNDAYS 11:00-17:00 (cabin-area exemption), so Sunday 12 July resupply works here. Mon-Thu/Sat 09:00-18:00, Fri 09:00-21:00. Address Panoramavegen 901, 2960 Røn. Also the check-in point for Vaset Camping (same phone/email: 61 36 30 55, joker.vaset@joker.no). [Norwegian grocery prices (Joker is ~10-15% above Kiwi/Rema)]</description><styleUrl>#s2</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.989,60.9961,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Kiwi Gol</name><description>grocery: Main resupply point, Sentrumsvegen 96 at the west end of the centre (on your way out toward Geilo). Confirmed OPEN SUNDAYS 09:00-21:00 (tourist-town exemption), so the Sunday 12 July closure problem does not bite in Gol. Weekdays 07:00-23:00, Sat 09:00-21:00. Gol is the biggest shopping town between Fagernes and Geilo: stock up here. There is also an Extra supermarket at Sentrumsvegen 128 as backup. [n/a]</description><styleUrl>#s2</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.94215,60.70151,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Joker Ustaoset</name><description>grocery: The resupply point. Haugastol has no grocery store, so this Joker at Ustaoset station (Ustaosvegen, by the rail line), 11 km east of Haugastol on your riding line from Geilo, is the last proper shop before Finse/Flam. Crucially it is open Sundays 11:00-18:00 (verified), which matters with 12 July 2026 falling on a Sunday: do not arrive before 11:00 expecting it open. Weekdays 10:00-18:00 (Fri to 20:00), Sat 09:00-18:00. Stocks daily groceries, propane, OTC medicines and local Hallingdal products. [Norwegian convenience-store prices (10-20% above Kiwi/Rema)]</description><styleUrl>#s2</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.0422,60.4989,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>No grocery store at Finse (resupply in Geilo)</name><description>grocery: Finse has zero shops: no Kiwi/Joker/Coop, nothing. Last proper supermarkets before Finse are in Geilo (Kiwi, Spar, Coop Extra), with a small shop at Ustaoset and a kiosk at Haugastol Turistsenter. Buy stove food and snacks in Geilo, and remember 12 July 2026 is a Sunday when Geilo groceries are largely shut (small sondagsapen exceptions aside). The lodges at Finse sell some chocolate/snacks but nothing you could cook from. Next real shop after Finse is in Flam. [n/a]</description><styleUrl>#s2</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.2062,60.5343,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Coop Marked Flam</name><description>grocery: The village grocery and your resupply point (chain: Coop). A-Feltvegen 18, near the cruise pier and train station, between the playground and the parking lot. Open Mon-Fri 08:00-20:00, Sat 09:00-18:00, and crucially Sun 12:00-18:00 (small-store exemption), one of the few Sunday-open groceries on the whole route. Stocks camping supplies. No alcohol sales on Sundays. [Standard Norwegian grocery prices]</description><styleUrl>#s2</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.116,60.864,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Extra Roros (Coop)</name><description>grocery: Main supermarket for resupply, Coop Extra at Havsjoveien 3 on the southern edge of town, on the way out toward the route. Long hours: Mon-Sat 07:00-23:00 and Sun 10:00-23:00 (Roros holds a tourist-place Sunday-trading exemption; Sunday opening confirmed by two listing services). Stock up here: limited resupply until Alvdal at km 163. [Standard Norwegian supermarket prices]</description><styleUrl>#s2</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.3751,62.5665,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Naerbutikken Tufsingdal (Mauritz Landhandel)</name><description>grocery: The resupply for this leg, on the route in Tufsingdal village roughly 20-25 km before Ellefsplass. Address Kopparleden 6075, 2555 Tufsingdalen, phone +47 477 00 083. Chain: Naerbutikken (NorgesGruppen), run by Mauritz Landhandel AS (org 920 776 213, active). Listed access 06:00-20:00 daily (Fri to 22:00) including Sundays via self-service/partially remote-operated shopping; staffed hours are shorter, and the self-checkout may want a Norwegian payment app, so aim for daytime. Also does parcel and medicine pickup. Last shop before the empty Orvdalen-Storlagda-Rendalen stretch. [Normal rural grocery prices]</description><styleUrl>#s2</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.73528,62.28638,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Extra Alvdal (Coop Extra)</name><description>grocery: Main supermarket for resupply, Nord-Østerdalsveien 5152 on the Rv3/Steimosletta strip, 200 m north of Frich's. Coop's own page confirms the store (phone +47 62 48 72 00) but does not publish weekly hours; expect roughly 07:00-22:00 Mon-Sat and verify locally. Closed Sundays under Norwegian trading law, so closed 12 July. Stock up here before the final ~3 km out to Gjelten Bru Camping; next shop on the route is Folldal (~30 km), then nothing until Dombas. [Cheapest chain in town]</description><styleUrl>#s2</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>10.616,62.1152,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Spar Alvdal</name><description>grocery: Second supermarket, at Steia 16 in the town centre a few doors from Huldra kafe. Confirmed operating (phone 62 48 76 00); also does hot food and take-away pizza. Closed Sundays. If you do hit Alvdal on Sunday 12 July, fallback food is Frich's (daily 08:00-23:00) or a fuel-station kiosk. [Slightly pricier than Extra]</description><styleUrl>#s2</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>10.6323,62.1084,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Extra Alvdal (Coop)</name><description>grocery: Main resupply for this leg: the last full supermarket on route before Grimsdalen, at route km 163 in Alvdal (Nord-Oesterdalsveien 5152). Coop's Extra chain, Mon-Sat 07:00-23:00, and listed Sunday-open 10:00-21:00 (self-checkout format; verify before relying on it for Sunday 12 July). Buy camp dinner/breakfast here if you plan to tent rather than eat at the hut. [Supermarket prices]</description><styleUrl>#s2</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>10.616,62.1152,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Coop Prix Folldal</name><description>grocery: Backup grocery in Folldal centre (Dovreveien 2), but it is an 8-9 km off-route detour west of Grimsbu along Rv29 (16-18 km round trip). Mon-Fri 07:00-23:00, Sat 08:00-21:00, closed Sundays, so useless on 12 July. Only worth it if you missed Alvdal and need proper resupply before the valley. [Supermarket prices]</description><styleUrl>#s2</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.9979,62.1318,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>KIWI Vaga</name><description>grocery: Main resupply, KIWI chain, Skogbygdsvegen 2 just off the Rv15 roundabout, 600 m from Smedsmo. Hours verified: Mon-Fri 07:00-23:00, Sat 09:00-21:00, CLOSED Sunday. If you arrive Sunday 12 July, buy Saturday or wait until 07:00 Monday before the Murudalen climb. Second supermarket: Coop Mega Vaga, Vagavegen 47 (Mon-Fri 07:00-23:00, Sat 08:00-21:00, also closed Sunday). Sunday fallback for basics: Circle K Vaga fuel station, Vagavegen 36 on Rv15. Last full supermarket before Beitostolen on this route, so load up for the Vinstre/Bygdin leg. [Groceries]</description><styleUrl>#s2</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.098,61.8737,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>KIWI 243 Beitostolen</name><description>grocery: Main resupply in Beitostolen (Ovrevegen 4A; 13 km down Rv51 from Bygdin, fast descent; ~24 km from Haugseter). Full-size supermarket and, critically, Sunday-open under the tourist-resort exemption: Sundays 09:00-21:00, Mon-Sat 08:00-23:00 (confirmed on kiwi.no, not 07:00 as previously listed). So even if you hit Beitostolen on Sunday 12 July you can resupply. There is no shop of any kind at Haugseter or Bygdin; last grocery before this stop is in Vaga, so carry food for the Murudalen-Vinstre leg. [Normal Kiwi supermarket prices]</description><styleUrl>#s2</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.9209,61.2429,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
</Folder>
<Folder><name>Sleep</name>
<Placemark><name>Tutjerne tarns wild camp (plateau above Beitostolen)</name><description>freecamp: Cluster of small swimmable tarns at ~1,050 m on the open plateau 2.5-3 km NE of the village, below Knausehogda (1,123 m) and Melbyfjellet. Location verified against Kartverket's official place-name register ('Tutjerne', group of tarns, Oystre Slidre, 61.2636 N 8.9267 E). Reached via Ovrevegen/Gronasvegen and a marked, checkpoint-numbered trail network from the centre (the Knausehogda-Tutjern loop is ~6.5 km; rideable gravel most of the way, short steep push at the start). Above the treeline on uncultivated stolsvidde well over 150 m from the nearest cabins, so allemannsretten applies. Popular day-hike picnic/swim spot with a rest area: arrive in the evening, pitch discreetly away from the trail, pack out everything. [Free | No booking. Max 2 nights in one spot under allemannsretten; expect wind and possible boggy ground after rain.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.9267,61.2636,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>First Camp Beitostolen - Valdres (ex Beitostolen Hytter &amp; Camping)</name><description>campsite: Official campsite at Finntoppvegen 2A, ~1.2 km SE of the centre on the way in from Fagernes, within walking distance of restaurants and shops. Open year-round (verified on First Camp's live site), taken over by the First Camp chain. Cabins plus tent/van pitches, service buildings, sauna, laundry, kitchen, mini-golf, outdoor chess, playground; hiking trails start from the site. Address geocodes exactly to the listed coordinates. [Tent pitch ~NOK 350-500 for two; cabins from ~NOK 1,000-1,500 | Tent pitches normally fine on arrival; cabins should be booked ahead for mid-July (Norwegian fellesferie starts then). Contact: beitostolen@firstcamp.no.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.9202,61.2413,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Bergo Hotell / Bergo Rom</name><description>hotel: Cheapest proper beds in the village: simple hotel rooms, apartments and cabins at Bygdinvegen 3782, dead centre, 100 m from SPAR and the restaurants. Doubles (incl. family rooms with sofa beds) listed from roughly USD 81-94 a night on aggregators (Kayak from $94, Planet of Hotels from $81), i.e. ~NOK 850-1,300. Many rooms face Slettefjell. Good drying/recovery option if the weather turns. Tel +47 61 35 10 00. [Double from ~NOK 850-1,300 | Book ahead for mid-July, especially Fri/Sat: Beitostolen is a busy summer hiking/cycling resort and the cheap rooms go first.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.9068,61.2481,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Wild camp at Nedre Leirungen (below Knutshøe)</name><description>freecamp: Classic legal wild-camp under allemannsretten: grassy shores of lake Nedre Leirungen in Leirungsdalen, beneath the Knutshøe ridge, reached by a short walk/push from Fv51 on Valdresflye about 4 km south of Gjendesheim (roadside pull-offs). Open uncultivated mountain terrain, far more than 150m from any building, with Gjende and Knutshøe views; a known photographers' camping spot. Note tents are explicitly not allowed in the Gjendeosen/Reinsvangen parking lots, so camp here or on the heath above the lodge instead. Coordinates are the lake centroid; pitch anywhere suitable on its shores. [Free (optional: pay 125 NOK at the DNT lodge for shower/facility access as a 'telter') | No booking; arrive before dusk for flat pitches, expect wind on the plateau]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.7954,61.476,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Besseggen Fjellpark Maurvangen</name><description>campsite: The official campsite for the area (Hoskelivegen 27), about 4 km from Gjendesheim by the Sjoa river at ~1000m. Tent pitches plus rental cabins, modern bathrooms, guest kitchen, on-site café, sauna and fire pits. Open year-round, check-in from 15:00. They guarantee arrivals by tent a spot, so it is the safe fallback in peak July. [Hiking tent incl. 2 persons 390 NOK/night in peak season (13 June-16 Aug); extra person 40 NOK; shower 5 NOK/min; cabins from ~400 to ~1650 NOK by size (book online) | Tent: no booking needed (spot guaranteed). Cabins: book well ahead for mid-July, Besseggen peak season]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.8455,61.489,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Gjendesheim Turisthytte (DNT)</name><description>dnt_hut: DNT's flagship staffed lodge (since 1878), ~185 beds in 1-, 2- and 4-bed rooms and dormitories, right at the Gjende boat pier and Besseggen trailhead. Showers included, linen rental available (sleeping bag liner required, rental 114-130 NOK). Summer season roughly early/mid-June to early October, operating 2026. The most atmospheric option and the only bed at the stop itself. [Dorm bed 290 NOK member / 382 non-member; 4-6 bed room 445/578; 1-3 bed room 515/670; full board (DNT pensjon) 1095-1315 member / 1430-1710 non-member (official 2026 prices) | Book ahead for mid-July (most visited lodge north of the Alps) at hyttebestilling.dnt.no; DNT tradition means nobody is turned away, worst case a mattress on the floor (186/300 NOK, only when all beds are taken)]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.8126,61.4943,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Bessheim Fjellstue og Hytter</name><description>hotel: Mountain lodge hotel about 5 km north of Gjendesheim overlooking Øvre Sjodalsvatnet: 27 rooms (64 beds, made beds, simple standard) plus 27 cabins/apartments (116 beds) with kitchenettes, sauna, canoe rental and a good restaurant. Summer season 5 June to 20 September 2026, on the Fv51 National Scenic Route. A comfortable cheap-hotel alternative if the DNT lodge is full. [Rooms from ~1100 NOK; cabins ~1850 NOK; breakfast ~210 NOK (2025 reference prices; confirm on booking) | Book ahead for mid-July via post@bessheim.no or +47 61 23 89 13; also on Booking.com]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.853,61.5146,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Tisleifjorden northwest shore (wild camp, Stølsvidda)</name><description>freecamp: Open mountain pasture (utmark) along the Mjølkevegen gravel road at the north end of Tisleifjorden (lake centre geocodes to 60.856, 8.947), roughly 1-2 km south of Langestølen. Treeless stølsvidda at ~820m with flat grassy shoreline pitches and lake water. Legal under allemannsretten: stay 150m+ from the stølar and cabins clustered at Langestølen, max 2 nights, and note Norway's general open-fire ban runs to 15 Sep. Riding 13 km past Vaset to camp here shortens the next day's stage to Gol. Closer alternative if you want to stay at Vaset itself: the lakeshore at Vasetvatnet is mostly ringed by cabins, so the paid campsite is the better option in the village. [Free | No booking. Carry water treatment or boil; lake and stream water.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.94,60.866,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Vaset Camping (Vasetsenteret)</name><description>campsite: Family-run campsite directly behind the Joker/Vasetsenteret at Vaset centre, ~800m altitude. Accepts tents plus ~70 motorhome pitches; showers (extra charge), toilets, guest kitchen (oven, 2 hotplates), laundry, WiFi. Check-in via the Joker supermarket (shared phone 61 36 30 55 and email joker.vaset@joker.no), which keeps long hours including Sunday. No rental cabins at the campsite itself (the similarly named Vasetdansen Camping with cabins is a different site in Tisleidalen, off your route, do not confuse them). Confirmed open year-round (1 Jan-31 Dec listing). [Tent pitch roughly 150-250 NOK (an older camper report cites 100 NOK/night, so expect modest), showers extra | Drop-in fine for tents, even in mid-July; check in at Joker Vaset.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.9905,60.9962,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Vasetstølen Hytter</name><description>cabin: Eight fully equipped cabins sleeping 4-9 persons each (per the official site, June 2026; older listings said nine cabins/65 beds), set in the historic farm courtyard near Vasetvatnet with the traditional restaurant on site, so dinner and breakfast are sorted without riding anywhere. Listed Mjølkevegen accommodation; cyclists explicitly welcomed. Open 1 June to 10 Oct. The charm pick if you want a roof and the best food at Vaset in one stop. [Price on request (small cabins typically ~1,200-1,800 NOK); phone +47 61 36 33 50 or +47 91 15 57 95 | Book ahead for mid-July (Norwegian holiday season); cabins sell out on summer weekends.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.9774,60.9934,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Gomobu Fjellstue</name><description>hotel: Family-owned mountain lodge at ~1,000m above Vaset on Valtjednvegen (toll road, ~40 NOK access fee, card accepted), 36 refurbished rooms plus 10 large cabins (3 bedrooms, private sauna). Official Mjølkevegen partner with ski/bike storage and bike rental. Restaurant serves traditional Norwegian dinner with local ingredients; non-guests can eat if they book ahead. Eco-Lighthouse certified. The comfort option: hot meal, sauna, real bed. Bookable on Booking.com with 2026 rates live. [~1,400-2,000 NOK per double incl breakfast | Book ahead for mid-July; it fills with hikers and Mjølkevegen riders. +47 61 35 77 10.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.9859,60.9807,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Wild camp: Golsfjellet heather plateau near Kamben</name><description>freecamp: The Hallingdal valley floor around Gol is fenced farmland (innmark), so legal wild camping in town is effectively impossible. Instead, stop on the open heather-and-birch plateau around Kamben on Golsfjellet (Kamben hamlet verified at 60.802, 8.979), just off the Mjolkevegen gravel road about 10 km / 550 vertical metres before the final descent into Gol. Utmark, allemannsretten applies; pitch 150 m+ off the road and away from the Kamben hamlet buildings and stol (summer farm) fences. Small tarns and streams for water, big views back over the plateau. Bikepacking.com's 'Of Milk and Navvies' route (Mjolkevegen + Rallarvegen) passes this exact stretch into Gol. Then it is a fast freewheel into Gol; remember the bakery is shut if it is Sunday. [Free | No booking. Avoid pitching inside summer-farm grazing enclosures; livestock roam freely up here.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.972,60.7995,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Personbråten Camping</name><description>campsite: Small family-run campsite on the bank of the Hallingdalselva (Rotneimsvegen 48), confirmed open year-round (ACSI: 1 Jan-31 Dec). 15 min walk to the centre and on the WEST side of town, i.e. zero backtrack when you leave for Geilo. 60-70 pitches with power; river swimming on site and Gol's main Mobrua swimming spot 120 m away. Sources conflict on huts: norcamp says no cabins, visitnorway mentions a few mobile bungalows for rent, so treat it as tent/van only. Some road and railway noise. GPS verified against norcamp listing. [Solo tent likely ~150-250 NOK; ACSI comparison price ~€34/night for pitch + 2 adults + car; van pitch 350 NOK incl. power (Aug 2025) | No advance booking needed for a tent, even mid-July; turn up and pitch. Phone +47 915 51 429 if in doubt.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.91931,60.69182,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>First Camp Gol - Hallingdal</name><description>campsite: Big full-service chain campsite at Heradvegen 189 (coordinates verified), 3 km EAST of the centre along the Rv7 (slight backtrack from your direction of travel). Tent pitches plus a large stock of cabins and apartments, on-site bistro, mini-market, jumping pillow, and the Hallingstampen outdoor pool with waterslide confirmed reopening for summer 2026 (renovated 2024). Summer weeks 27-32 have included family activities and a 'stay 3, pay for 2' promotion. The comfort option if you want a cabin night and a swim. [Tent pitch ~350-450 NOK (estimate); cabins from ~900-1,800 NOK in high season (book for exact rates, not published on site) | Cabins should be booked ahead for mid-July (Norwegian summer weeks 27-32 are peak); tent pitches are normally available but can be pre-booked with pitch selection on firstcamp.no. Contact gol@firstcamp.no / +47 32 07 41 44.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.00517,60.69986,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Pers Hotell</name><description>hotel: Three-star family resort hotel right in the centre (Sentrumsvegen 72, coordinates verified). Not fancy but comfortable: pool/waterpark area, breakfast included (buffet gets consistently good reviews), secure bike storage on request, and Erik's Grill &amp; Sportsbar plus the main restaurant downstairs for dinner. The realistic hotel night in Gol; the town has no hostel or DNT hut. [Double from roughly 1,600-2,500 NOK/night incl. breakfast in July (aggregators show from ~USD 159-260) | Book ahead for mid-July; Norwegian fellesferie (industrial holiday) starts around 10 July and Gol fills with family traffic.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.94812,60.70057,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Haugastol Turistsenter (apartments + mountain rooms)</name><description>hotel: The obvious roof at Haugastol: modern 4-bed (Type A/B) and 8-bed (Type D) apartments with kitchens, plus two budget shared 'mountain rooms' (8 bed spaces total) for those happy to share. Restaurant, coffee bar, bike shop and Rallarvegen bike rental on site; full-service mode (reception + meals) through July, with half-board available as an add-on for mountain rooms. Note: sleeping bags are not permitted in the mountain rooms, bedding rents on arrival. [Rates shown only in booking flow; apartments roughly 1,500-2,500 NOK/unit, mountain room is the budget option. Dinner ~390 NOK, breakfast ~175 NOK | Mid-July is peak Rallarvegen season and this is the route's main start point: book weeks ahead via haugastol.no or +47 32 08 75 64.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.8531,60.5124,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Fagerheim Fjellstugu</name><description>hostel: Family-run fjellstugu on Rv7, ~12 km by road southwest of Haugastol (a 30-40 min ride with loaded bikes, off the Rallarvegen line but an easy out-and-back). Dorm bed 850 NOK pp or double room 1,050 NOK pp, both including made bed, towels, breakfast AND a three-course dinner at 19:00: strong value for hungry riders versus Haugastol. DNT members get 5% off accommodation. Open year-round (verified on official site, including holidays), operational for 2026. [Dorm 850 NOK pp, double 1,050 NOK pp, half board included | Book ahead for mid-July. Cancellation: free more than 14 days out, 50% charge 8-14 days out, 100% charge within 7 days of arrival. Check-in 15:00-18:00 (call +47 922 58 498 if later). Note: no self-catering allowed at Fagerheim.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.7852,60.4396,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Wild camp: open heath off Rv7 toward Fagerheim</name><description>freecamp: Open, treeless heath with lakes and streams on the Hardangervidda edge, ~4 km southwest of Haugastol beside Rv7 toward Fagerheim. Flat tent-friendly ground, water from lakes and streams, and legal under allemannsretten provided you stay 150 m+ from the scattered cabins (tents are explicitly not permitted in the cabin fields immediately around Haugastol and Finse). Critical caveat: do NOT camp along the first 13 km of Rallarvegen from Haugastol toward Finse or around Finse itself, that corridor is off-limits, so pitch south of Rv7, not on the cycle route. [Free | No booking; exposed at 1,000m+ so expect wind and possible single-digit temps even in July.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.826,60.483,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Wild camp: south shore of Finsevatnet (across the dam)</name><description>freecamp: The one sanctioned wild-camping zone at Finse. Camping is only allowed on the south shore of Finsevatnet because the lake is the settlement's drinking-water supply; signs at Finse mark where you can pitch. Cross the small dam at the lake outlet near Finsehytta and pick a grassy flat along the shore west of the hut, well away from cabins. Flat-ish, watery, exposed at 1,200m; expect mosquitoes in fine weather and possible snow patches even mid-July. Standard allemannsretten rules, max 2 nights. Bonus: walk back to Finsehytta for dinner and a Finse 1223 beer. [Free | No booking; arrive and pitch. Bring a 4-season-ish setup, nights can hit low single digits in July.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.4975,60.5968,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Finsehytta (DNT staffed lodge)</name><description>dnt_hut: Large staffed DNT lodge (sleeps 200+ including overflow mattresses), 300m from the station across the lake outlet. Bunk rooms and dorms, shared showers, drying room, and the full-board package includes breakfast, packed lunch and a 3-course dinner: ideal rider fuel. On-site microbrewery. The closest thing to a campsite-with-services Finse has; there is no official campsite in the village. 2026 summer season opens 26 June. [Full board (bed + breakfast + 3-course dinner + lunch + shower): dorm 1,060 NOK DNT member / 1,390 NOK non-member; rooms 1,200-1,275 / 1,580-1,660 NOK pp. Price list dated 2023, expect modest increases. | Book ahead for mid-July via hyttebestilling.dnt.no, Rallarvegen peak season. DNT members are never turned away even when full (mattress on the floor). A DNT membership pays for itself across a multi-hut trip.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.507,60.5979,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Hotel Finse 1222</name><description>hotel: The historic ~44-room railway hotel on the platform (where parts of The Empire Strikes Back were filmed). Sauna, bike rental and workshop, drying facilities, restaurant and bar. The splurge option after days in a tent. Open through summer and going year-round from 2026. [Roughly 3,000-3,500 NOK per night for two including 3-course dinner, breakfast buffet and packed lunch (recent guests report ~USD 325/night packages). | Book well ahead for mid-July; it is the only hotel at Finse and fills with Rallarvegen cyclists and hikers.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.5031,60.6018,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Flamselvi river flats below Berekvam (wild camp)</name><description>freecamp: Don't wild camp in Flam itself: the valley floor around the village is farmland and built-up, and locals confirm camping around the village is not tolerated. Instead, stop short on your descent from Myrdal: grassy and gravel flats beside the Flamselvi around Berekvam (the Flamsbana passing-loop station, 343.8m, ~10.5km from Myrdal). This mid-valley stretch is uncultivated gorge between the farms at Kardal above and Hareina below, right on the Rallarvegen road. Keep 150m+ from the station buildings and any cabin, max two nights, leave no trace. Free under allemannsretten. [Free | No booking. Pitch late, leave early; the spot is beside the cycle road so expect passing riders in daytime.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.0965,60.7895,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Flam Camping &amp; Hostel</name><description>campsite: Award-winning family-run campsite and HI hostel ~300m from the station, right where the Rallarvegen rolls into the village. ~80 tent pitches on terraced grass (some sheltered, power available, picnic tables and grills), hostel rooms, and cabins with and without bathroom; new sanitary block and kitchen completing for the 2026 season. Explicitly welcomes bikers and hikers; camp kitchen and laundry on site. This is the default bikepacker stop in Flam. [Tent NOK 400/night; hostel rooms from NOK 990 (shared bath) to NOK 1,200 (private); cabins from NOK 1,030 (2BR w/ bath NOK 2,800) | Mid-July is peak season in one of Norway's busiest tourist villages: book hostel rooms and cabins several weeks ahead. Tent pitches are more flexible but arrive by mid-afternoon.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.1167,60.8597,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Fretheim Hotel</name><description>hotel: The historic 122-room hotel at the head of the fjord, in business since the 1800s. Not cheap, but the end-of-trip splurge option: fjord-view rooms, big breakfast, Restaurant Arven upstairs, and secure bike storage on request. Recent guests report around NOK 2,800/night for a double; aggregator rates for peak season run higher, roughly USD 340-500. [~NOK 2,800-4,500/night double in July | Book well ahead for mid-July; Flam sells out when cruise and tour traffic peaks.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>7.113,60.8612,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Hittersjoen northeast tip (wild camp)</name><description>freecamp: Shoreline at the far northeast tip of Hittersjoen lake, ~2.7 km NE of the town centre: follow Fv31 Brekkveien out of town along the north side of the lake, then lakeside tracks/paths (Borta Sjoa, Malmveien) to the NE end. Flat pine-heath pitches, swimmable lake. This spot is 300m+ from the nearest mapped building; note the east and south shores nearer town are lined with cabins (Sjohaga'an) and a farm (Strommevollen) sits NE of the lake, so do not pitch there. Legal under allemannsretten on uncultivated land, max 2 nights. No facilities; fill water in town. Do not pitch inside the UNESCO town itself. [Free | No booking; allemannsretten rules apply (150m from inhabited houses, leave no trace).]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.4261,62.5904,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Roros Camping Moen (ex Haneset Camping)</name><description>campsite: The town campsite at Havsjoveien 131, ~2 km southwest of the centre by the Glomma river. Tent pitches plus cabins and motel rooms: basic 4-person cabins from 660 NOK, small 2-person cabins 900-1100 NOK, larger serviced cabins with shower/WC 1190-1680 NOK, single motel room 560 NOK, motel family room 800 NOK (all confirmed on the official site). Reception 09-22, online booking on their site. [Tent pitch 380-500 NOK; cabins 660-1680 NOK | Tent pitches are normally walk-up fine; book cabins ahead for mid-July, Roros is a busy UNESCO destination in summer.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.3516,62.5677,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Rorosvidda Hotell (ex Idrettsparken)</name><description>hotel: The budget hotel option, formerly Idrettsparken Hotell (rebrand confirmed by local press and an active 2026 Booking.com listing), at Ora 25, a 4-minute walk from the historic centre and ~500m from the station. Simple rooms with private or shared bath, breakfast typically included, free parking and secure spot for bikes on request. Roughly 1000-1400 NOK per double depending on room type and date (aggregators show from ~$104-132). [~1000-1400 NOK/double | Book 2-4 weeks ahead for mid-July; small property and Roros fills up in summer.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.381,62.5708,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Vertshuset Roros (rooms)</name><description>hotel: Step-up option if you want one comfortable night before 705 km of gravel: historic inn rooms above the best restaurant in town, Kjerkgata 34, breakfast included (served Wed-Sun 07:30-10:00). Part of the Roroshotellene group; booking engine live for summer 2026. [~1600-2200 NOK/double | Book ahead for mid-July; it is the most sought-after address in the historic centre.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.3867,62.5763,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>DNT Ellefsplass (self-service cabin)</name><description>dnt_hut: The stop itself: a converted farmhouse run by DNT Oslo og Omegn in Oversjodalen (Tolga municipality) with 8 beds, electricity, running water and a full bathroom on the ground floor, unusually plush for a self-service hut. Open 1 Jun-10 Sep annually (confirmed on ut.no). Bedding base provided, bring a sheet liner. [NOK 340 member / 520 non-member (2026 price list, confirmed) | Book ahead for mid-July: only 6 of 8 beds are pre-bookable on hyttebestilling.dnt.no (cabin id 10831), the other 2 are drop-in. Booked beds are released if you have not arrived by 19:00. Pay via DNT app. With 8 beds a booking is cheap insurance even if drop-in usually works on a Thursday.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.44822,62.20446,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Wild camp, south shore of Oversjoen tarn</name><description>freecamp: Open heath and pine ground on the south/east shore of the Oversjoen tarn (Kartverket: tjern at 62.2279, 11.4854, Tolga), right beside the road you ride into Oversjodalen from Tufsingdalen, about 3 km northeast of Ellefsplass. Utmark, roughly 800 m from the nearest farm (Oversjoen gard at 62.2344, 11.4831), so comfortably legal under allemannsretten (150 m rule). Lake water for filtering, good swimming. Alternative: pitch beside the hut itself, but the 2026 DNT price list explicitly says campers using the cabin after 18:00 pay full lodging. [Free | No booking. Standard allemannsretten rules: max 2 nights, leave no trace, no open fire 15 Apr-15 Sep.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.4868,62.227,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Lillemoen holiday house, Oversjodalen</name><description>cabin: Fully renovated small farmhouse in the village, about 1 km east of Ellefsplass. Sleeps 5 (two double bedrooms plus a single loft bed), washing machine, dishwasher, full kitchen. Active Airbnb listing ('Lillemoen - Great Nature', Tolga), also promoted on visitnorway.com and roros.no. The comfortable fallback if the DNT hut is full or you want a proper indoor night. [Whole house, rate on Airbnb (not published; expect typical Norwegian whole-cabin pricing well above the DNT hut) | Book on Airbnb in advance; whole-house listings in this area go early for July.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.46552,62.20909,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Jonasvollen Camping</name><description>campsite: The nearest official campsite: caravan pitches, tent space and camping cabins at Femundsenden, the south tip of Lake Femunden, with marina, boat hire and kiosk. Open year-round per jonasvollen.no. Off-route, roughly 9-12 km east of Tufsingdal village (so about 25-30 km before Ellefsplass); only makes sense if you want a shorter day 1 and a lakeside night on Femunden rather than pushing to the hut. [Tent pitch price not published; small Norwegian sites typically NOK 150-300. Phone +47 414 03 216 / +47 62 49 89 94 (Kjell Magne) or +47 476 41 937 (Nina Alice) | No advance booking needed for a tent in mid-July; call ahead for a cabin.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>11.874,62.232,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Gjelten Bru Camping</name><description>campsite: The stop itself: riverside campsite at Sølndalsveien 15, ~3.5 km northwest of Alvdal centre and directly on the route toward Folldal/Grimsdalen. Verified: 13 cabins, 45 powered pitches, modern sanitary block, kiosk, TV lounge, playground. Camping season 20 May - 1 Oct; cabins year-round. Coin showers (NOK 10+), washing machine NOK 60, bedding rental NOK 60. Cabin prices confirmed on the official site: NOK 490 (simple 4-bunk, bring sheets/liner), NOK 690 (insulated 2-room), NOK 990 (modern 6-berth with kitchen and own shower/WC). [Tent + 2 riders est. NOK 150-250 (not published, confirm on arrival); cabins NOK 490-990 verified | Site states no reservation needed for tents. For a cabin in mid-July, call/email a few days ahead: +47 973 23 588, post@gjeltenbrucamping.no.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>10.5682,62.1313,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Wild camp: riverbank pine flats near Gjelten bru</name><description>freecamp: Flat pine-and-heath terraces along the riverbank ~400-500 m upstream of the Gjelten bridge, opposite side from the campsite. Caution: this point reverse-geocodes to the Masshaugen farm area (Plassen), so scout on the ground and keep the legal 150 m from any inhabited house or farm building; camp only on open forest utmark, max 2 nights under allemannsretten. River water available (treat it). National open-fire ban applies 15 April - 15 September; use a stove. Realistically only if the campsite is full or you want a free night, since the official site is a few hundred metres away with showers. [Free | No booking; standard allemannsretten rules. Verify the exact pitch on arrival, terrain not desk-verifiable.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>10.566,62.127,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Steien Hotel og Skydsstation</name><description>hotel: Restored 1878 coaching inn at Steia 20 in Alvdal centre, the characterful splurge option: 12 unique rooms (21 beds), all with private shower/WC, breakfast included, 2-course dinner for guests from local ingredients, English-inspired garden. Confirmed operating with 2026 prices on Booking.com and Agoda. Phone 975 70 175, post@steienhotel.no. [Approx NOK 1,500-1,900 double incl. breakfast (verify at booking) | Book ahead for mid-July; only 12 rooms, weekends fill.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>10.6315,62.1084,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Frich's Hotell og Spiseri Alvdal</name><description>hotel: Motel-style rooms attached to the Frich's diner at Nord-Østerdalsveien 5148, Steimosletta. Functional rooms with private bath; food downstairs 08:00-23:00 and breakfast 07:00-10:00. The cheapest indoor bed in Alvdal and the practical bad-weather bailout. Confirmed listed on Booking.com, Trivago and aggregators. [From ~NOK 1,100-1,400 double | Walk-in usually fine midweek, but book online for July weekends.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>10.6174,62.1144,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Grimsdalshytta (DNT Oslo og Omegn staffed hut)</name><description>dnt_hut: 54 beds at 1,000 m between Rondane and Dovre national parks, right on the route at km 230. Staffed summer season 19 June - 13 September 2026 confirmed on the DNT site, so fully operating mid-July. Shower, drying room, food service, card payment. Bed-only rates (incl. shower) per the official 2026 DNT Oslo og Omegn price sheet: dorm 290 NOK member / 382 non-member, 4-6 bed room 445/578, 1-3 bed room 515/670. Full pension (bed, breakfast, 3-course dinner, packed lunch of 4 bread slices) 1,095/1,430 in dorm, up to 1,315/1,710 in 1-3 bed room. Sheet liner required, rent 114 NOK member / 130 non-member; own sleeping bags not allowed as bedding. [Dorm 290-382 NOK bed only; full pension 1,095-1,430 NOK pp (dorm) | Book online at hyttebestilling.dnt.no; mid-July is peak and reserving is sensible, but DNT staffed huts never turn anyone away (floor mattress 186/300 NOK, only offered when all beds taken). The self-service annex (19 beds) closes permanently after Easter 2026 as a wild-reindeer measure; the staffed summer operation continues unaffected. Contact: grimsdalshytta@dnt.no, +47 45 29 81 55.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.6418,62.0912,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Grimsdalshytta teltplass (tent pitch at the hut)</name><description>campsite: The hut has a designated tent area (teltplass listed among its 14 facilities on ut.no). 125 NOK member / 160 non-member per person (official 2026 price sheet line: teltere/tilgang til hyttefasiliteter) buys access to hut facilities including shower and toilets. Best-value play for two riders with a tent: pitch here, then buy the 3-course dinner and breakfast inside. Remember you cannot eat brought food inside the hut or run your own stove at the hut itself. [125-160 NOK pp + meals | No booking needed for tenting; pay the warden. Book dinner on arrival (served 19:00).]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.6425,62.091,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Wild camp: Grimsa riverbank flats east of the hut</name><description>freecamp: Open heath and grass flats along the Grimsa river, roughly 1.5-2 km east (back) along Grimsdalsvegen from the hut, well over 150 m from the hut and the nearest seter buildings. The Grimsdalen landskapsvernomraade regulation (verneplan for Rondane, vedlegg 3, 122.5 km2) restricts motor traffic and caravan parking but does not prohibit ordinary tenting, so normal allemannsretten applies. Flat pitches, river water, fishing in the Grimsa (licence needed). Free; no facilities. Cook here rather than at the hut. [Free | No booking; standard allemannsretten rules (150 m from inhabited buildings, leave no trace). Move on after a night or two and avoid disturbing grazing animals and reindeer.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.675,62.0855,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Grimsbu Turistsenter Motell &amp; Camp</name><description>campsite: Fallback if you stop short of the hut: full-service campsite at the eastern toll-road entrance, route km ~205 (25-30 km and most of the climb before Grimsdalshytta). Cabins in all sizes (large ones with shower/WC), motel rooms, tent and caravan pitches, cafeteria, on-site supermarket, communal kitchen, sanitary block, bathing lake, playground. Open year-round; listed on camping.no and ut.no. [Tent ~300 NOK for 2; basic cabins from ~600 NOK, en-suite cabins more (confirm on grimsbu.no) | Drop-in fine for tents; phone +47 62 49 35 29 or mail@grimsbu.no for cabins in July.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>10.1714,62.1554,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Smedsmo Camping</name><description>campsite: The stop itself: family-run campsite beside Rv15 on the edge of Vagamo (Vagavegen 80), 700 m from the square. Coordinates verified against NorCamp (61.869778, 9.103056). Tent pitches on flat ground, service building with showers, kitchen, washing machines, WiFi. Prices verified on smedsmo.no: tent 230 NOK (280 with electricity), tent + car 320 NOK; 1-room cabin (3-4 pers) 690 NOK + 290 washout, 2-room (4 pers) 790 NOK + 340 washout, flats 1150 NOK + 420 washout. Open through summer (service building closes only Nov-Easter). Tent pitches first-come; cabins for mid-July 2026 bookable now and worth reserving, Vagamo is busy Jotunheimen-gateway territory in fellesferie. [Tent 230-320 NOK (2 riders + tent), cabin 690-790 NOK + washout 290-340 | Tents: no booking needed (first-come). Cabins: book ahead for mid-July at reservations.visbook.com/6978.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.1031,61.8698,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Wild camp: Vagavatnet south shore west of Klones</name><description>freecamp: Plausible allemannsretten spot: forested shoreline on the quiet south side of Vagavatnet, west of the Klones farm peninsula (Klones confirmed on the lake shore near the village, reached over Finnbrue or via the side road off Rv15 about 2 km out). Pine/birch woods and lake access; stay 150+ m from buildings and off cultivated fields around Klones. Uncultivated outfield, one to two nights fine; no facilities, take water from the lake or fill bottles in town. Coordinates approximate and geometrically consistent with the south shore; pick your exact pitch on the ground. [Free | No booking; standard allemannsretten rules (150 m from dwellings, max 2 nights, leave no trace).]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.056,61.8665,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Villa Vaga (Classic Norway Hotels)</name><description>hotel: The mid-range hotel option: historic village hotel in the centre of Vagamo, 67 rooms, restaurant, bar, indoor pool, sauna, breakfast included. Verified operating 2026 (villavaga.no, Booking.com). Aggregator rates from USD 157-183, so budget roughly 1500-2000+ NOK per night for a July double; the original 1300-1800 estimate was optimistic for fellesferie. [Double ~1500-2000 NOK incl breakfast | Book ahead for mid-July; it is the main hotel in a Jotunheimen gateway town and fills in fellesferie.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.0958,61.8746,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Bokhandel'n Gjestehus</name><description>hotel: Guesthouse rooms above the bakery/restaurant at Vagavegen 45 on the square: listed on Booking.com as Bokhandel'n - by Classic Norway Hotels (4-star), family rooms with private bath, garden, restaurant downstairs, 24h front desk. Reclassified from hostel to hotel: this is a small upscale guesthouse, not budget dorm accommodation. Rates about USD 167-250, roughly 1700-2600 NOK. Pricier than Villa Vaga but you sleep above the best food in town. [Room ~1700-2600 NOK | Book ahead for mid-July 2026 via Booking.com; only a handful of rooms.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.0941,61.8751,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Wild camp, Vinstre north shore east of Haugseter</name><description>freecamp: Open mountain utmark at ~1,030 m along Jotunheimvegen, about 1-1.5 km east of Haugseter on the north shore of Vinstre: flat heath and grass down to the lake, easy water access, big views. Fully legal under allemannsretten; OSM reverse-geocodes the spot to the Perslettstolen seter area (isolated dwellings only), so pitching 150 m+ from cabins is easy. Exposed above treeline, so stake well. Fishing permits and an evening meal available 15-20 min walk away at Haugseter. [Free]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>9.003,61.3408,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Haugseter Fjellstue tent pitch</name><description>campsite: The fjellstue takes tents on its grounds: 415 NOK per tent per night, shower 69 NOK (both confirmed on haugseter.no; motorhome 525 NOK), restaurant and limited facilities on site. The pragmatic choice: camp cheap, eat the game-and-trout dinner inside. Generator off 23:00-07:00, so charge electronics at dinner. [415 NOK/tent/night + 69 NOK shower | Tent pitches are not bookable online; turning up before the restaurant closes at 20:00 is the practical approach, or call +47 61 34 15 10 to be safe.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.984,61.3424,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Haugseter Fjellstue (rooms and cabins)</name><description>hotel: Family-run staffed mountain lodge on the north shore of Vinstervatn, 60 beds across rooms, apartments and cabins (ut.no confirms 60 beds, betjent). Private, not DNT-run, but ut.no states it gives a discount to DNT members, so bring your card. Room with breakfast 1,429 NOK pp; half board (breakfast, packed lunch, dinner) 1,839 NOK pp; cabins 1,390-2,235 NOK per night plus 319 NOK pp bedding/towels (all confirmed on haugseter.no). Season 19 June to 27 September 2026 confirmed on their own site, so mid-July is squarely in season. [B&amp;B 1,429 NOK pp; half board 1,839 NOK pp; cabins 1,390-2,235 NOK/night + 319 NOK bedding | Book ahead for a bed in mid-July: only 60 beds and it fills with Mjolkevegen cyclists, anglers and Jotunheimen hikers. Phone +47 61 34 15 10 or haugseter.fjellstua@gmail.com (both confirmed).]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.984,61.3424,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
<Placemark><name>Bygdin Hoifieldshotel</name><description>hotel: Historic mountain hotel at the east end of lake Bygdin, oldest wing built 1897 (confirmed on bygdin.com history page), ~11 km past Haugseter: the fallback if Haugseter is full or you want to bank a few more km. Summer season early June through the first week of October (their own info page), so mid-July is open. Proper restaurant with 3-course evening dinners, plus the daytime sommerkafe 11:00-18:00. Half-board rates require 2+ night stays (confirmed); single nights room-and-breakfast, bookable direct or via booking.com (2026 rates live, doubles from roughly 1,700 NOK). [Roughly 1,500-2,500 NOK/double B&amp;B depending on room; half board only for 2+ nights | Book ahead for mid-July weekends: +47 61 34 14 00 or booking@bygdin.com (both confirmed on bygdin.com). Listed with 2026 prices on booking.com.]</description><styleUrl>#s3</styleUrl><Point><coordinates>8.8011,61.3276,0</coordinates></Point></Placemark>
</Folder>
<Style id="route"><LineStyle><color>ff1f35c8</color><width>3</width></LineStyle></Style>
<Folder><name>Route</name>
<Placemark><name>Røros→Flåm (RWGPS 41496641)</name><styleUrl>#route</styleUrl><LineString><tessellate>1</tessellate><coordinates>11.3814,62.57469,0 11.38701,62.57215,0 11.38562,62.5702,0 11.37809,62.56695,0 11.37726,62.56543,0 11.38404,62.56328,0 11.3952,62.55958,0 11.40704,62.55443,0 11.41462,62.55087,0 11.41893,62.54618,0 11.42697,62.54262,0 11.4372,62.53882,0 11.44517,62.53475,0 11.45034,62.53219,0 11.45795,62.52863,0 11.47071,62.52474,0 11.48203,62.52193,0 11.49428,62.52107,0 11.50353,62.52075,0 11.51205,62.51847,0 11.52329,62.51707,0 11.53244,62.51485,0 11.53995,62.51179,0 11.54604,62.50975,0 11.55345,62.50694,0 11.55791,62.50308,0 11.56628,62.50011,0 11.57407,62.49709,0 11.58027,62.49403,0 11.58409,62.49322,0 11.58921,62.49139,0 11.59843,62.49076,0 11.60817,62.48653,0 11.61612,62.48317,0 11.62385,62.47947,0 11.62649,62.47738,0 11.62883,62.47561,0 11.63266,62.47347,0 11.63748,62.47039,0 11.64197,62.46716,0 11.64534,62.46519,0 11.64876,62.46174,0 11.65246,62.4577,0 11.65399,62.45296,0 11.65393,62.45,0 11.65327,62.44848,0 11.65145,62.44667,0 11.65092,62.4447,0 11.64921,62.44142,0 11.64664,62.43906,0 11.6455,62.43748,0 11.6454,62.43655,0 11.64676,62.43436,0 11.65017,62.4328,0 11.65132,62.43135,0 11.65313,62.43001,0 11.6577,62.42744,0 11.66194,62.42588,0 11.66532,62.42387,0 11.66745,62.42066,0 11.67004,62.41836,0 11.67209,62.41697,0 11.6728,62.4154,0 11.67525,62.41344,0 11.67573,62.41163,0 11.67522,62.4082,0 11.67799,62.4052,0 11.67796,62.40295,0 11.67988,62.40022,0 11.68351,62.39806,0 11.68419,62.39473,0 11.68761,62.39412,0 11.68892,62.39281,0 11.69217,62.3905,0 11.69332,62.38857,0 11.6958,62.38643,0 11.69862,62.38397,0 11.69988,62.38121,0 11.70273,62.37913,0 11.70413,62.37627,0 11.70565,62.37426,0 11.70799,62.37066,0 11.7107,62.36781,0 11.71236,62.36594,0 11.71456,62.3646,0 11.71652,62.36267,0 11.71944,62.35963,0 11.72586,62.35758,0 11.72815,62.35349,0 11.73083,62.35097,0 11.73329,62.34701,0 11.73468,62.3437,0 11.73415,62.34095,0 11.73429,62.33921,0 11.7348,62.33